2. Scientific Thought-styles: Corpus analysis of early English medical
writing in a variationist frame
The Scientific Thought-styles project’s original research plan and questions of interest
influenced the corpus design from the very beginning. In a nutshell, the project aims
at describing stylistic change in medical English in a long diachronic perspective in a
multifaceted sociohistorical framework. The general frame of our approach is varia-
tionist, ie. we examine variation in linguistic usage, aiming to explore and identify
linguistic and language-external factors that condition and determine the choice of a
specific linguistic variant among the possible alternative ways of saying the same thing.
This aim rests on the variationist paradigm, according to which variability in language
```
is, or may be shown to be, structured (Milroy & Milroy 1997: 47). A wide range of fac-
```
```
tors cause variation, “orderly heterogeneity” (Weinreich et al. 1968), in the linguistic
```
choices of speakers and writers, including, for example, the context of discourse, the
participants of the communicative situation, their social and regional backgrounds
```
and their interpersonal relationship, and the purpose of the communicative act (see
