Our research making use of the first two corpus components, MEMT and
EMEMT, has shown, however, that in early English medical writing, a clear-cut
dichotomy between scholasticism and empiricism is far too simplified a view of the
textual reality. In fact, changes in medical writing, including the scientific paradigm
they reflect, come about gradually and in a much less conspicuous way than has been
generally assumed. In the early modern period, only texts at the learned end were truly
innovative cutting-edge writings adopting an empirical mindset, while the old ways of
thinking and the linguistic practices connected with medieval patterns were replicated
in most English medical texts of the period. This multifaceted view of the register has
only been facilitated by the analysis of large quantities of data in corpora like MEMT
and EMEMT, which represent the entire register of medical writing.
3. Representing the bulk and variety of English medical writing
in the early modern period
As a principled and systematically collected dataset, EMEMT aims to be a represen-
tative sample of medical texts printed between 1500 and 1700. “Representativeness’,
used here in the standard corpus-linguistic sense, refers to “the extent to which a sam-
```
ple includes the full range of variability in the population” (Biber 1993: 243; see also
```
```
e.g. McEnery et al. 2006). Achieving this kind of representativeness in Early Modern
```
English medical writing implies familiarity with the text population which the corpus
is intended to represent, including its language-external sociohistorical and disciplin-
ary background. As a textual domain, medicine in early modern England is a rich
field, containing writing representing different genres, traditions and varieties of texts,
Introducing Early Modern English Medical Texts
created and used for various purposes by writers and readers from different social and
educational backgrounds in a wide range of domain-specific contexts during a 200-
year time-span.
The period covered in the corpus is characterized by major sociocultural changes,
some of them affecting the contemporary society at large, like the position of English,
```
the increasing literacy, the development of print culture or changes in the world view;
```
others more focused on medicine as a social domain and a special area of knowledge
and praxis. During this period, the domain of medicine was undergoing a major lan-
guage shift. By 1500, English had emerged in medical writing from the shadow of
Latin in the first wave of a pan-European process of vernacularization in science and
```
medicine that began in non-institutional contexts (see e.g. Voigts 1989; Taavitsainen &
```
```
Pahta 1998; Pahta & Taavitsainen 2004). By 1700, vernacularization had reached an
```
entirely new stage: English had also challenged Latin as the language of institutional
