```
regulations were often issued, such as the orders given in the name of Elizabeth I
and the Privy Council in 1578, laying out a consistent practice of public health and
social control to the whole kingdom during the time of a plague. While the preven-
tion of plague and other infectious diseases remained an important function of public
health throughout the period, health in society always meant much more than fighting
against infectious diseases.
The growth of cities and the increasing resources of states and territories shaped
public health mechanisms as forcefully as did theories of medicine and exigencies
```
of epidemic disease. The role of the town physician (medicus civilis), who worked
```
together with civil officials in taking care of the medical and sanitary affairs of a town,
can be traced back to the late Middle Ages. Medical conditions outside towns tended
to be more haphazardly organized and supervised, and resident medical health off-
cers appeared much later in rural areas. This lack of professional medical help in the
countryside provided a market for remedybooks and other medical advice targeted at
“House-holders in the Country, who are either farre remote, or else not able to enter-
```
taine a learned Physician” (Wood, Alphabetical book, 1639: title page).
