century, they took on more assignments. Under the impact of mercantilist and cam-
eralist teachings, the health of the population became a central interest of the state.
Detailed plans for the minute regulation of health and human welfare were compiled.
In these projects two issues were always important: one was the need to ensure that
enough medical personnel were available to serve the population and the other was
to examine and license practitioners. Already by 1550, three corporations tried to
control medical practice in London: the Society of Apothecaries, the Barber-Surgeons
Company, and the College of Physicians. By the late seventeenth and early eighteenth
centuries, the task of licensing was given to the new-style collegia medica, most of
```
which were set up by state authorities to function as boards of health (Lindemann
