6. Innovation and tradition: What changed in early modern medicine?
At the beginning of the eighteenth century, the academic European outlook on the
natural world had changed tremendously from what it had been in 1500. The new
ideology of natural knowledge was now firmly associated with potential practical and
operational applications, whereas the aim during the peak of humanism had been the
recovery of classical civilization. In 1700 the authorities of antiquity competed with
advocates of new claims to natural knowledge that justified themselves through their
“method” instead of any classical precedent. “Knowing how” had started to become as
```
important as “knowing why” (Dear 2001: 168-170).
```
These changes in the whole idea of science and natural philosophy naturally had
their effects in the field of medicine as well. Harold Cook has neatly summarized the
changes that took place in the outlook of academic medicine from the Middle Ages to
the end of the seventeenth century as follows:
The fine structures of the body had been distinguished and their movement,
growth, and changes were being charted. At the same time, the causal analyses
that Avicenna had used had been fundamentally challenged. In the process much
had changed: humors had disappeared, whereas bodily fluids, even lymph, had
```
grabbed attention; it no longer mattered whether someone's temperament was
```
sanguine or choleric, for her physiology was the same as her neighbor’s. Not
only had the basic principles of physic been undermined, opening new questions
to study, but certainty had become to rest on knowledge of material detail.
```
(Cook 2006: 432)
```
This process of overturning the ancient authorities was by no means painless and early
modern medical writing is characterized by a wide variety of controversies over both
theory and treatment. Paracelsian remedies and Helmontianism, Harvey’s theories on
the circulation of blood, and new methods in the treatment of venereal diseases all
inspired advocates of both the old and the new to express their views in writing, result-
```
ing in a lively debate over their dangers and virtues (see the category description of
```
```
SPECIFIC TREATISES in Part II for more details on this literature).
```
```
