The new synthesis of medical knowledge was derived on the one hand from
detailed observations and investigations and on the other from the concern for utility
in fighting disease. The new medical tradition tried to create a rationally based system
of pathology and therapeutics, and to critically reexamine the empirical tradition. For
the moderns, the fight against disease came before the preservation of health. Simulta-
neously, there developed a medical profession that tried to establish clear boundaries
between itself and non-professionals. This profession based its claim to acceptance not
only on experience but also on the mastery of a scientific medicine not accessible even
```
to educated laymen (Mikkeli 1999: 98).
```
Among other things, medicine tried to adopt from natural philosophy the idea of
mathematical and measurable methods. The Paduan Professor of Medicine Santorio
```
Santorio (1561-1636) was the culmination point of the commentary tradition of clas-
```
```
sical medical texts. At the same time, however, in his Ars de statica medicina (1614),
```
Santorio for the first time tried to lay the foundations for a new “statistical medicine”
which rested on a measurable basis. In the aftermath of Newton's ideas on mathemati-
cal physics, British academic physicians tried to adopt Santorio’s “statistical medicine”
```
into Britain during the first part of the eighteenth century (Mikkeli 1999: 113-118).
```
However, the modernity of medicine around 1700 should not be overemphasized.
The medical marketplace saw the ubiquitous presence of a wide variety of healers, and
the persistent myth about the paucity of medical practitioners in early modern society
has been shown to be fallacious:
The landscape literally swarmed with them in every conceivable form: physicians,
surgeons, midwives, cunning-folk, bonesetters, dentists, licothomists, bathmasters,
apothecaries, pastors and ordinary people who busied themselves with medicine
either as part of their normal household chores or as expressions of good
neighborliness. Ideas of what constituted a “good healer” turned on many variables
```
and medical choice was always to a degree idiosyncratic. (Lindemann 1999: 232)
```
Professionalization was not a key issue. Far more important, especially in the eigh-
teenth century, was the growing world of consumer choices and the proliferation
of products, services, and information that finally undermined the older corporate
world. But it was not until the nineteenth century when the “laboratory revolution”
took place in medicine, and bacteriology and other biomedical considerations became
more important for the medical profession, that the classical ideas of the art of medi-
cine were totally abandoned.
