```
Institutional developments gave an incentive to new beginnings in scientific writing,
as the history of science reached a new phase in England when, following the Resto-
ration, the Royal Society was founded in 1660. By this time the written word in the
printed form had achieved a leading role in communicating science. Members of the
new, close-knit discourse community made a conscious decision to communicate their
```
scientific findings and opinions in writing in the new PT (1665-). Its practices have
```
```
attracted a great deal of attention (Atkinson 1999; Valle 1999; Moessner 2008; Gotti
```
```
forthcoming). In 1664 a committee was established to purify and regulate the language
```
```
of science and fix its style, but it “hardly met” (Blake 1996: 246-247).”° Nevertheless, the
```
Royal Society chose English as the main language of communication, and formulated
```
guidelines for writing styles. The work of John Wilkins (1614-1672), one of the found-
```
ers of the Royal Society, aimed at clear and logical language, in which findings of the
```
Society could be presented unambiguously (Blake 1996), with one word corresponding
```
```
to one meaning in a stable way (see Gotti 2003). Thomas Sprat (1635-1713), author of
```
```
The History of the Royal Society (1667), stated the principles of a simple style of writing.
```
The proclamation states:
... to reject all the amplifications, digressions, and swellings of style: to return
back to the primitive purity, and shortness, when men deliver so many things,
almost in an equal number of words. They have exacted from all their members, a
```
close, naked, natural way of speaking; positive expressions; clear senses; a native
```
```
easiness: bringing all things as near the Mathematical plainness, as they can: and
```
preferring the language of Artizans, Countrymen, and Merchants, before that, of
```
Wits, or Scholars. (Sprat 1667: 113)
