```
nostications stretches back for centuries, following set conventions acquired in the
late medieval period. The old attitude to knowledge with certainty is reflected in these
texts throughout the early modern period. The aftermath of medieval science lives on
in popular adaptations of the homo signorum and other astrological doctrines to broad
and heterogeneous readerships even today.
6. Conclusions
Scientific and medical writing became more diversified in the early modern period as,
on the one hand, medieval writing conventions derived from Graeco-Roman models
became established and continued in use, and on the other hand, new developments
took place. The first medical guilds were founded in the late medieval period, and the
societies of learned doctors of medicine in the early sixteenth century. Medical writing
broke away from medieval conventions little by little, but some layers of writing con-
tinued the old traditions. The process began in the latter half of the sixteenth century,
but as the examples from later periods show, old veins of thought continue throughout
the period. New practices emerged in publishing as anonymous writings gave way
to known authorship by learned physicians, surgeons, and other educated men. By
this time, sociohistorical conditions changed with increasing prosperity that allowed
upper middle class men to devote time to scientific pursuits and form new types of dis-
course communities. This led to the foundation of the Royal Society, and the learned
scientific community adopted new forms of communication. In most text categories,
however, not much changed and, for example, the textbook category remains fairly
stable throughout the two centuries.
Discourse and genre dynamics in Early Modern English medical writing 53
Earlier studies have focused on the learned treatises of the period and dealt with the
text type features of the upper layers of the register. The new resource EMEMT offers
a broad range of texts in a readily available form and the picture can be complemented
by writings for more heterogeneous audiences including common people for whom the
almanac provided the source of medical knowledge that everyone should master.
An incentive for the break-away from the old came from the broadening horizons
of the world, new knowledge based on observation, and a growing lack of faith in the
wisdom of ancient authorities. The broadening of the world created a new kind of litera-
ture with eye-witness accounts giving different evidence about nature than the descrip-
tions in inherited accounts. New knowledge diffused slowly through layers of scientific
writing, working within the old frame, but combining with new modes of thought.
