of representativeness, there is a keen awareness that this goal is difficult to reach for
```
several reasons (see e.g. McEnery et al. 2006).
```
Firstly, because a corpus is a selection of texts, the criteria followed in its com-
pilation will necessarily have a fundamental impact on all studies conducted using
that resource. In order to avoid drawing conclusions that the corpus does not justify,
it is imperative that researchers using a given corpus are familiar with the principles
```
that guided its compilation (see Rissanen 1989). In simple terms, we need to know
```
what types of texts a corpus, or a specific part of a corpus, is intended to represent. To
that end, the following chapters provide information on each part of the corpus from
this perspective. To give an example, although EMEMT can be said to represent writ-
ten medical texts of the early modern period, practical reasons made it necessary to
limit the selection to printed texts. This is an essential piece of information for users
when it comes to understanding what domains of writing the corpus represents, par-
ticularly since handwritten materials were also circulated widely at the time and they
were of great importance in several fields of medicine, in the dissemination of recipes
```
for instance (Leong & Pennell 2007). Compared to the manuscripts, printed texts argu-
```
ably carried higher prestige and also brought along a more explicitly commercial aspect
to the production of medical texts. Within the medium of print, EMEMT covers a vast
range of different types of medical writing, and the compilers firmly believe that the
volume and variety of texts in each of the main categories is sufficient to give a fair
representation of the principal features in a major field of early modern medicine.
Secondly, representativeness must be understood in the correct historical con-
text. The underlying sociohistorical reality of EMEMT is reflected e.g. in the fact that
the vast majority of texts in the corpus were written by men. Very few printed medi-
cal texts of the early modern period were written by women, and thus the apparent
