University of Tampere/ University of Helsinki
SPECIFIC TREATISES is the largest category in EMEMT, with the total of 71 texts and
609,961 words, comprising 30 per cent of the entire corpus. Texts in the category rep-
resent the bulk of early printed books on medicine, covering a broad range of topics
in a variety of styles. The aim in compiling this corpus category has been, on the one
hand, to include a wide array of different types of texts in order to reflect the full
scope and diversity of the text population, and, on the other hand, to provide some
diachronic continuity by including multiple texts on the same topics in order to record
language-external changes in disciplinary knowledge and practice.
The defining principle for the inclusion of texts in this category is a specific focus
on a single topic, such as an individual disease, method or therapeutic substance, or
a specific field of medicine, like childbirth and children’s diseases. To provide a finer
analytical grid, this large category has been further divided into five subcategories
based on the nature of this focus:
a. texts on SPECIFIC DISEASES (e.g. syphilis, agues, melancholic diseases)
b. texts on SPECIFIC METHODs of diagnosis or treatment (e.g. urinoscopy, astrology,
```
phlebotomy)
```
c. texts on SPECIFIC THERAPEUTIC SUBSTANCES (e.g. nitre, mithridatium)
texts ON MIDWIFERY AND CHILDREN’S DISEASES
e. texts On PLAGUE.
The category is closely related to the first corpus category, GENERAL TREATISES. In
MEMT, earlier counterparts of texts in these two EMEMT categories appear in a
single category, that of “Specialized texts’, but with the increased bulk and diversity
of vernacular writing in the early modern period, these two subtypes of texts have
been divided into separate categories. The key difference between the two EMEMT
categories is the scope of the text. Although many actual samples extracted from
textbook-like comprehensive treatises on medicine in GENERAL TREATISES bear a
close resemblance to the samples in spECIFIC TREATISES, there is a defining differ-
ence in the surrounding textual context of the samples in the two categories, which
74 Paivi Pahta & Maura Ratia
is also reflected in their names. While the samples in the first corpus category are
always extracts of larger general treatises, discussing the principles of medicine as a
whole, the samples in sPECIFIC TREATISES are taken from individual and indepen-
dent treatises focusing on a specific aspect of medicine. The same defining prin-
ciple, a focus on a single topic, distinguishes texts in the subcategories of sPECIFIC
METHODS of diagnosis and treatment and sPECIFIC THERAPEUTIC SUBSTANCES from
the therapeutic compendia included in the corpus category of RECIPE COLLECTIONS
```
(see p. 103 below).
```
The earliest text in specIFIC TREATISES dates from 1525. After that the chron-
ological coverage extends over the whole period, with a clear emphasis on the
seventeenth century. Only six texts date from the first half of the sixteenth cen-
tury. This, however, reflects the reality in the actual text population, as only a few
specialized texts were printed in English before 1550. The majority of texts in this
category were originally composed in English, although texts originally written
in Latin and other European vernaculars are also included. The discourse forms
vary, but most texts can be described as expository or narrative, including case
reports, while some texts are explicitly instructive. Argumentative and promo-
tional texts, such as pamphlets and advertisements, are also included. The samples
vary in length, and comprise both extracts and complete treatises. The target audi-
ences also vary, ranging from strictly academic specialists to the widest general
readership. The writers come from different social and educational backgrounds.
Most texts are written by university-educated physicians, other medical practi-
tioners, such as apothecaries or midwives, or medical students, but the category
also includes texts written by laymen and members of the clergy. A few texts are
anonymous.
