2.2 Criteria for inclusion
In their general approach to medicine, texts in this subcategory bear a resemblance to
a range of other categories, but they have been assigned to this particular subcategory
because of their restricted focus on a single method. A variety of methods is repre-
sented by the texts, including the diagnostic and therapeutic methods already familiar
in medieval medicine, such as urinoscopy and phlebotomy, which held their position
```
in standard medical practice throughout the period (Wear 2000: 120-121, 139-140;
```
```
Porter 2001: 168). During the sixteenth century, the medical applications of astrol-
```
ogy were also highly appreciated, and, for example, in the mid-seventeenth century
it provided the bedrock of the medical theories of the highly popular medical writer,
```
Nicholas Culpeper (Wear 2000: 355; see below). Towards the end of the period, how-
```
ever, the advocation of astrology as a diagnostic or therapeutic method had become
part of the more popular layers of writing. Physiognomy, the assessment of a person's
character from their facial appearance, is represented by one text in the subcategory.
Its earlier medical application was largely disregarded in the early modern period,
Category 2. Treatises on specific topics 81
but like astrology, it lived on in literature aimed at a general readership. The position
of alchemy was also changing, but in a different way. In the seventeenth century it
became an integral part of the rise of Paracelsianism and iatrochemistry, eventually
```
giving rise to a new discipline, chemistry, with its medical applications (see e.g. Linden
```
```
2003). Texts on new inventions and practices in diagnosis and therapy are also repre-
```
sented. These include the use of medicinal baths, various minerals, acids and alkalis,
new purges and laxatives, and the newly-discovered warming stone, curing numerous
ailments.
The medical works of the bestselling and most prolific medical author and
```
translator of the seventeenth century, Nicholas Culpeper (1616-1654), are rep-
```
resented by three extracts in this subcategory. Two samples come from the
immensely popular School ofphysick, a collection of texts published posthumously
in 1659. Culpeper’s intention was to provide vernacular medical texts so that med-
ical knowledge would not be the sole preserve of learned physicians. Because of
this politically radical view and his own lack of formal education, Culpeper was
```
in constant conflict with the College of Physicians (Wear 2000: 355-356; Fissell
```
```
2004: 4, 135-142).
```
