2.6 Continuity from medieval traditions versus new trends
The continuity from the medieval traditions is seen in texts like Epitomye of phisi-
ognomie, “gathered out of Aristotle, Rasis, Formica, Loxius, Phylemo[n], Palemo[n],
Consiliator, Morbeth the Cardinal and others many moe, by that learned chyrurg-
```
ian Cocles: and englished by Thomas Hyll Londoner” (Cocles 1556: title page). The
```
same applies to early texts on urinoscopy, phlebotomy and astrology, which continue
the transmission of mainstream methods of diagnosis and therapy from the Middle
Ages. The medieval heritage became, however, increasingly challenged in the course
of the 200-year period, and this ideological shift is also reflected in the texts in this
subcategory. New Paracelsian theories and practices gain visibility in Hester’s Key of
```
philosophie (1596). The challenged Galenic principles of physiology receive support
```
```
in Thomas Cock’s Miscelanea medica (1675), which compares Galenic and chemical
```
84 Paivi Pahta & Maura Ratia
medicine and argues against the claims posed by chemists by emphasizing the Galenic
system, i.e. the balance of humours and elements.
New argumentative genres appear in this subcategory, including pamphlets and
```
advertisements (see Ratia and Suhr forthcoming). A case in point is John Colbatch’s
```
```
Physico-medical essay concerning alkaly and acid (1698), where the author presents his
```
claims and also supports his views in the language of the new and experimental phi-
losophy, arguing for the usefulness of “ocular demonstrations” over university learn-
```
ing. Experiments are reported and advocated in Tauvry’s Treatise of medicines (1700).
```
Several authors explicitly claim that they correct erroneous, in many cases old, views
and practices. For example, the title page of the second part of William Turner's Great
```
herbal, from which the Booke of bathes (1562) is extracted, claims that the work cor-
```
rects “diuerse confutationes of no small errours, that men of no small learning haue
committed in the intreatinge of herbes of late yeares.”
2.7 Images
Most texts in this subcategory have illustrations. Urinoscopies contain images of
urine flasks, a tradition of medical illumination carried over from manuscripts,
where standard sets of coloured urine flasks commonly accompany urinoscopies
```
to aid practitioners in diagnosis, prognosis and therapy (see e.g. Jones 1998). In
```
```
Seynge of uryns (1525), urine flasks are only used for text-organizing purposes at
```
```
the beginning of new paragraphs; all flasks in the book are empty. Two mainly dec-
```
```
orative images of urine flasks are contained in Recorde’s Vrinal of physick (1547),
```
which also contains an anatomical illustration of the male urinary system. Cocles’s
```
Epitomye of phisiognomie (1556) contains several images of human heads and faces
```
and relies heavily on the combination of word and image. Similar interplay is also
```
seen in Gesner’s Treasure of Evonymvs (1559), a richly illustrated alchemical book,
```
which contains images of herbs, and tools for practising alchemy, including various
kinds of flasks and furnaces, many of them portrayed in use, heated over open fire
```
and steaming. Astrological treatises, e.g. Culpeper’s Semeiotica uranica (1658) and
```
```
Joseph Blagrave's Astrological practice of physick (1671), contain various tables for
```
astrological calculation and figures on astrological judgments, some of them labelled
as tables “of logistical logarithms”. The charts and tables form an integral part of the
text, and are crucial for its usability. Culpeper’s books also show his portrait and coat
of arms as a frontispiece.
