Texts in the subcategory are quite evenly spread, although the earliest text was
published only in 1574. There is also a gap in publications during the Civil War
years in the 1640s and 1650s. Advertisements for proprietary medicines emerge
only in the late seventeenth century, and they form the majority of the texts after
the 1660s.
3.2 Criteria for inclusion
Treatises on SPECIFIC THERAPEUTIC SUBSTANCES consist of a wide variety of rem-
edies, Plant, animal and mineral remedies frequently occur in writing in the six-
teenth and seventeenth centuries, and this tripartite division “of plants, of metalles,
```
and of liuing things” (Baker, Oleum magistrale, 1574: 9r) is often specifically stated
```
in the corpus texts. Remedies form a significant part of the published medical lit-
```
erature of the time (Wear 2000: 46, 78), but this also refers to recipe collections
```
and books on materia medica, which are included in the category RECIPE COLLEC-
```
TIONS (see next chapter). Texts on SPECIFIC THERAPEUTIC SUBSTANCES differ in
```
that they concentrate on a single substance, e.g. nitre, or types of substances, e.g.
86 Paivi Pahta & Maura Ratia
mineral waters, whereas RECIPE COLLECTIONS are more varied collections of cures.
The present subcategory contains plant remedies — peppers, quinquina bark and
```
tobacco (two texts) - and mineral remedies. The latter consist of simples - i.e. nitre,
```
```
Diacatholicon aureum (gold powder), Sal solutivum (mineral salt) -, mineral waters
```
```
(two texts) and compound medicines, i.e. Oleum magistrale and mithridatium. In
```
addition, there are advertisements for the compound proprietary medicines Pil-
```
lulae radiis solis extractae, Elixir salutis (two texts) and Nendick’s popular pill. The
```
division into simples and compounds is central and often discussed in the texts.
The following excerpt manifests the idea of simples as a starting point in medicine,
```
an idea which was shared especially by Galenic and Helmontian physicians (Wear
```
```
2000: 49):
```
```
(12) Therfore it is necessary to haue good knoweledge in the nature and qualitye of
```
simples, wherof medicens haue their beeing. For without the knowledge therof:
it is not possible to doo any thing in this art, and especially in the cure of
Sinewes worthy commendation. It suffiseth not to haue great store of
Receipts, except ye knowe the particuler nature of euery simple. And with
hauing knowledge: he shalbe able to frame his composition him self, according
as the nature of the greef shall require. ... So then it is necessary to knowe the
nature and facultye of Simples whiche is amply shewed in many good Bookes and
```
especially by Galen in his Booke of Simples. (Baker, Oleurm magistrale, 1574: 9r-v)
```
Pure simples as God's gifts could, however, be further “corrected”, as Galenists called it,
```
or chemically purified, a method preferred by Helmontians (Wear 2000: 49, 100-102):
```
```
“;+. in smal quantitie Tabacco may be taken of any man without peril or imminent
```
```
danger, & especially being corrected & purified by the force of the fire” (Philaretes,
```
```
Work for chimny-sweepers, 1602: Flv). Remedies were clearly a matter of debate and
```
several issues were discussed in relation to them, e.g. Galenists proposed mostly herbal
```
remedies, whereas Paracelsians advocated chemical medicines (Wear 2000: 46). The
```
matter of simples versus compound medicines was also often raised: “It is an Error
```
in Physick to make a hodge-podge of a great many ingredients (though they be much
```
```
of the same efficace) to satisfie one and the same indication” (Talbor, English remedy,
