3.4 Vernacularization and relation to other languages
The texts in the subcategory were originally written in the vernacular and they
represent a less scholarly end of the scale in EMEMT. The only exceptions to the
```
vernacular are Oleum magistrale (1574), and English remedy (1682), both translated
```
from French.
3.5 ‘Target audience
The target audience is wide, with the exception of two scholarly texts on mineral
```
waters — Natvrall bathes (1631) and Qveenes welles (1632) ~ both with frequent
```
```
passages in Latin, which are often not translated; the latter text also contains Greek
```
and very long commentaries in the margins. However, most texts in the category
```
have clearly a wider intended audience, e.g. the title page of Mithridatium (1585)
```
claims that the text was “Compiled rather for those which are to vse it, then for the
learned”. This idea of usability is conveyed by the reader-friendly and handbook-
like format of most texts. Nevertheless, the intended audience was the middling
and upper class rather than the poor, who are only mentioned in passing in a few
texts. Remedies were often associated with money and expensive and exotic novel-
```
ties were generally considered more effective (Wear 2000: 69). Nitre is described
```
as “A drugge so rare and precious, as by the great price and small plentie thereof,
```
is knowen vnto you” (Chaloner, Vertue of nitre, 1584: 1v), and one author draws
```
```
attention to “the extreame rate, and price of the Indian Tobacco; of which the great-
```
est part is sold for ten times the value of pepper, and the best of it, weight for
```
weight, for the finest siluer” (C. T., How to plant tobacco, 1615: A4r). The extrava-
```
gant prices of some of the remedies resulted in new measures being proposed, e.g.
planting tobacco in England, so “the treasures exchanged for Tobacco, may be kept
```
within the Land” (C. T., How to plant tobacco, 1615: Blv; see Wear 2000: 72 for the
```
Category 2. Treatises on specific topics 89
```
discussion of foreign vs. local drugs).* The medical works on new exotic plants,
```
```
e.g. tobacco, were likely to attract a wider readership (Siraisi 2007: 225). The adver-
```
tisements also had a wider audience due to their function as “early modern infor-
mercials’, designed to be read aloud in street-corners, and thus including even the
```
uneducated masses (Fissell 2007: 120, 126), but the price of the medicines would
```
have excluded the truly poor.
3.6 Continuity from medieval traditions versus new trends
The surge in remedy texts in medical literature was a new phenomenon of the
sixteenth century, resulting from the inclusion of northern European drugs into
```
herbals and the rediscovery of the drugs of antiquity (Wear 2000: 67).The wide
```
interest in new territories and discoveries is also characteristic of the period,
```
reaching beyond strictly medical topics like new drugs and new diseases (Siraisi
```
```
2007: 225). The desperate need for new medicines was the driving force behind
```
```
exploring for new remedies (Brooks 1952: 35-36), and the belief in panaceas lent
```
credence to seeing therapeutic value in a variety of plants and other substances.
America became the source of new therapeutic plant substances, and to a lesser
degree animal remedies, prized at that time for their medicinal value. Among these
were tobacco - soon to become the most profitable export from the New World
- sarsaparilla, sassafras, coca, guaiacum and quinquina bark (de Asta & French
```
2005: 91).
```
On the textual level, the traditions of herbals and materia medica can be seen in
information structures, especially in texts about herbal remedies.
