The ten texts included in the category are unevenly distributed across the period
because of gaps in the actual text population. Few relevant titles appeared during the
sixteenth century, and in midwifery in fact fewer texts were available in the first cen-
```
tury of print than in manuscript the century before (Fissell 2004: 7); in the corpus
```
they are represented by only two texts from the 1540s. The remaining eight texts are
dispersed across the seventeenth century.
4.2 Criteria for inclusion
This subcategory contains excerpts from a variety of texts dealing with the praxis of
human reproduction, including childbirth, childcare and problems associated with the
reproductive system - the special fields of medicine today known as obstetrics and
midwifery, pediatrics, and gynaecology. Some texts also provide information on cur-
rent reproductive theory, including the male and female reproductive anatomy and
physiology, the development of the foetus, aetiology and pathology. The texts include
extracts from midwives’ handbooks, covering a wide range of topics concerning preg-
nancy, labour and conception. Some texts focus on particular difficulties or condi-
```
tions in the reproductive organs, such as hysteria. Self-help books are also included;
```
these were a popular genre among texts dealing with women’s sicknesses, consid-
ered a private and delicate area of health, which for reasons of decorum could not be
Category 2. Treatises on specific topics 91
comfortably discussed with male physicians. Another popular genre represented in
the subcategory was sex advice literature, ie. guidebooks providing advice on sexual
etiquette and the generation of offspring, which started rolling off the presses in Eng-
```
land and elsewhere in western Europe from the seventeenth century onwards (Porter
```
```
& Hall 1995: 33).
```
4.3. Discourse form
Texts on MIDWIFERY AND CHILDREN’S DISEASES are generally instructive texts, aimed
to provide advice on medical practice. Instructions on procedures are often provided
in straightforward didactic prose, almost as commands directed to the practitioner or
the patient, as in many texts in the other practice-oriented corpus categories:
```
(16) And yf it chaunse that (the labor drawynge nere) she waxe faynte or syckelye:
```
