4.4 Vernacularization and relation to other languages
Most texts in this subcategory go back to foreign originals, but since midwifery and
post-natal care as fields of medicine are practice-oriented, the Latinate tradition is not
```
prominent. For example, the earliest text in the category, Byrth of mankynde (1540),
```
is a translation from the Latin version of an originally German midwifery manual,
```
Der swangern Frawen und Hebammen Rosegarten (1513), a best-seller of its time.
```
Richard Jonas, the English translator, emphasizes the role of the vernacular in the
production of the original, saying that it was written by a physician “in his owne
```
mother tunge, that is beyinge a German, in the German speche” (Roesslin, Byrth of
```
```
mankynde, 1540: ABii’). The other sixteenth-century text, Thomas Phayer’s Boke of
```
```
chyldren (1546) is translated from French. Seventeenth-century texts contain both
```
translations from French and original compositions in English, including two par-
ticularly important original works in English by Nicholas Culpeper and Jane Sharp
```
(see Section 4.6 below).
```
4.5 Target audience
The subcategory includes both texts aimed at medical practitioners and the general
```
readership. Aristoteles master-piece (1684) is probably one of the most widely-read
```
texts in the corpus, targeted at the widest possible readership, and apparently reach-
ing it: it is characterized as one of the most popular sex manuals ever published,
running into multiple revised editions from the seventeenth to the turn of the twen-
```
tieth century (Porter & Hall 1995: 33). Several texts are aimed at female practi-
```
tioners, ie. midwives, or more generally at women readers. Jacques Guillemeau’s
```
Child-birth (1612), translated from French, is addressed to both young surgeons
```
and midwives. Pemell’s De morbis puerorum, a systematic manual of children’s dis-
```
eases illustrated in example (19) above, is written “for the benefit of such as do not
```
understand the Latine tongue, and very useful for all such as are house-keepers, and
```
have children” (1653: title page), while John Sadler characterizes his Sick womans
```
looking-glasse as a methodical treatment of “all uterine affects, or diseases arising
```
from the wombe; enabling women to informe the physician about the cause of their
```
```
griefe” (1636: title page).
```
4.6 Continuity from medieval traditions versus new trends
Continuity from the medieval traditions of writing is perhaps best illustrated in this
```
subcategory by the anonymous Aristoteles master-piece (1684), which discusses the
```
reproductive health of women, the formation of the foetus, midwifery, the genital
organs and conception and pregnancy. It is based on knowledge and materials that
94 Paivi Pahta & Maura Ratia
circulated in medieval manuscripts in Latin and various vernacular languages, and
contains a layered hotchpotch of materials drawn from various sources, giving advice
on a large number of reproductive concerns that were of interest to ordinary peo-
```
ple (for its discourse features, see the chapter on discourse and genre dynamics by
```
```
Taavitsainen in this volume). Its later versions added names of the most famous latest
```
theorists or invoked the Royal Society here and there, but in general the text com-
municated a combination of the earlier medieval and ancient theories of reproduction
```
with folklore (see Porter & Hall 1995: 33 ff.; Cody 2005: 99).
```
Advances in other areas of medical knowledge, in anatomy and physiology in
particular, influenced the knowledge base of human reproduction and pediatrics.
During the period covered in the corpus this also caused significant social changes in
disciplinary practices. The most dramatic change affected the role of women practitio-
ners as birth-attendants. Until the seventeenth century, assisting childbirth was almost
universally a woman's job: midwives advised and attended the expectant mother, and
female friends and relatives would arrive for the birth. Although most texts on mid-
wifery were written by men, they were only allowed to be present at the scene of birth
```
in case of emergency (Cody 2005: 3; see also Evenden 2000). This began to change
```
towards the end of the seventeenth century in a dramatic shift which has been called
a “revolution in obstetrics’, leading to the birth of obstetrics as a scholarly discipline
```
(Wilson 1995: 1). A new kind of practitioner appeared on the scene after the French
```
```
model: the man-midwife, the accoucheur, a male practitioner who assisted not only in
```
emergencies but also in normal births. By the early eighteenth century, men-midwives
```
had set up obstetric practices in several urban centres in England (see Wilson 1995;
```
```
Cody 2005; Pahta forthcoming b).
```
The early phases of these new trends are represented by Nicholas Culpeper’s
```
Directory for midwives (1651), which offered a new way of writing about reproduc-
```
tion and babies. His book addressed this delicate topic in a jocular style, “without
```
shame and without worrying about the potential for corrupting male readers” (Fis-
```
```
sell 2004: 4-5). He was the first midwifery writer to discuss both male as well as
```
female bodies in print, presenting female bodies as inferior to male — a notion that
is already present in earlier scientific writings on generation and embryology. Cul-
peper also emphasized the social aspects of reproduction, including the socially sig-
nificant questions of paternity.
The subcategory also includes the first printed midwifery manual written by
a woman, Midwives book by Jane Sharp, who in the preface describes herself as a
“practitioner in the art of midwifery above thirty years”. First published in 1671, the
book became a bestseller, and by 1725 was in its fourth edition. Sharp addressed a
wide range of issues considered relevant to human reproduction, including concep-
tion and the promotion of fertility, the signs of pregnancy and the care of expectant
mothers, the management of normal deliveries and malpresentations, the treatment
Category 2. Treatises on specific topics 95
of venereal disease, and the post-natal care of both mother and baby. The book also
provided information about the anatomy of the male and female reproductive organs,
and a short discussion of children’s diseases. According to Sharp, her book was based
on her own experience and her reading of foreign authors, but recent research has
```
shown that she in fact borrowed from several works of Nicholas Culpeper (see e.g.
```
```
Moscucci 2004).
```
4.7 Images
Several midwifery manuals contain foetus-in-utero illustrations, i.e. images of babies
in the mother’s womb in different positions. These images belong to an old tradition of
```
medical illumination (see e.g. Jones 1998; see also Tebeaux & Lay 1992). A number of
```
```
foetus-in-utero images are contained in Guillemeau’s Child-birth (1612), while Sharps
```
```
Midwives book (1671) has a full-page woodcut of a female figure with a dissected womb.
```
Later versions of the book include other types of anatomical illustrations and scenes
from the birth-chamber. A nursery scene is depicted as a frontispiece in Sadler's Sick
```
womans looking-glasse (1636). Birth-chamber scenes and anatomical illustrations are
```
also found in later versions of Eucharius Roesslin’s Byrth of mankynde, whereas the first
edition sampled for EMEMT from 1540 only contains a decorative woodcut framing
```
the title page and decorated chapter initials. Culpeper’s Directory for midwives (1651)
```
includes a single image of a foetus, some astrological tables, and Culpeper’s portrait and
```
coat of arms as a frontispiece. Aristoteles master-piece (1684) contains some woodcuts
```
of people with “birthdefects’, including the famous frontispiece portraying “The Effi-
gies of a Maid all Hairy, and an Infant that was born Black by the Imagination of their
Parents, etc.”
5. Texts on PLAGUE
PLAGUE texts comprise about 3 per cent of the EMEMT texts, with 9 texts and 63,461
words. Fissell has calculated that approximately 4 per cent of the published medical
```
literature in 1640-1740 was written about plague (2007: 116). This low figure may
```
demonstrate the weakening of the epidemics in the late seventeenth century.
5.1 Chronological coverage
Plague treatises were written during or right after the visitation of the pestilence. The
outbreaks in the sixteenth century were very frequent, occurring almost every decade,
but in the course of the seventeenth century epidemics became more intense and the
publication of plague treatises peaked during these big epidemics. There are only two
texts from the sixteenth century in this category, from 1539 and 1578, which do not
