The divine origin of all physical ailments was often mentioned only with regard to
plague and venereal disease. Therefore, books on plague have a deeper religious tone
```
than those on other non-epidemic infirmities (Kocher 1953: 269, 266).
```
Plague treatises are important because plague was seen as “the disease of diseases”
and thus representative of other diseases. For example, corruption and poison, or
```
venom, are discussed at length in four texts, Myrrour or glasse of helth (1539), Poore
```
```
mans iewel (1578), Treatise of the plague (1603) and Physick for the plagve (1636).
```
