5.3. Discourse form
Plague treatises are a mixture of different text types and styles. Texts were typically short,
```
even under 5,000 words, although this was not always the case (see Wear 2000: 278).
```
```
Certain necessary directions (1636) is the only large work — a collection of official docu-
```
ments for the prevention of plague of which the first book of nine is included in the
corpus. Six texts employ religious argumentation, which often occurs at the beginning
in discussions about the causes of the pestilence, the sin of mankind being the primary
one. The style echoes that of the pulpit, which shows the familiarity of medical writers
```
with religious treatises on plague (Wear 2000: 278). A significant number of authors in
```
the material were not physicians but clergymen, including Thomas Moulton, Thomas
Brasbridge and James Balmford. For example Balmford, representing the Church of
England, discusses in Plagves infection the moral implications of the pestilence and
the duties of ministers and physicians in dialogue form, emphasizing the avoidance of
```
contagion: “Christ hath sent vs not to visite the sicke, but to preach” (1603: 18). There
```
```
are even prayers in some of the texts, e.g. three long ones in Food and physick (1665),
```
separately “For those that are not Visited” and “For those that are Visited”. Only after
98 Paivi Pahta & Maura Ratia
“the Great plague” of 1665 did the religious element, conspicuous especially in the
```
prefaces and introductions, decline (Wear 2000: 278).
```
Due to the gravity of the disease and the lack of an efficient cure, a lot of space in
plague treatises is dedicated to preserving one’s health against the pestilence, which
draws on traditional medical knowledge from the regimen genre. Medical writers were
familiar with the medical topology of the regimens and could identify the environ-
```
mental sources of plague (Wear 2000: 301). Practical regimen-style advice occurs in
```
```
six texts throughout the period. Physick for the plagve (1636) is the only one to discuss
```
```
all six non-naturals in a manner typical of regimens (see the chapter on REGIMENS).
```
More often only some of the non-naturals are treated, especially diet with the emphasis
on moderation. Another common theme in plague treatises is discussions about fear,
e.g. in Physick for the plagve: “because of all Passions, Feare is the most pestilently per-
```
nicious” (Bradwell 1636: 37). A remedy is suggested in Plain and easie method:
```
```
(22) Therefore Wine and Confidence are a good Preservative against the Plague:
```
But when the Spirits, through fear, or want of supply, do recede, and are forcd
to give back, the Enemy enters, and first seizeth them, and thence gets into the
```
Blood and Humors; Therefore much Fasting and Emptiness are bad: ...
```
```
(Willis, Plain and easie method, 1691: 7)
```
The texts without the regimen type of discourse are also dissimilar in other ways:
```
Plagves infection (1603) is a religious dialogue; Certain necessary directions (1636) is a
```
```
collection of official documents, the corpus extract consisting mostly of recipes; and
```
```
Food and physick (1665) is a mishmash of recipes, prayers and religious “meditations”
```
and general advice, e.g. “To Smell to: The Root of Enula-Campana, steeped in Vinegar,
and lapped in a Handkerchief, is a special thing to smell unto, if you come where the
```
Sickness is” (T. D. 1665: 6). This type of general advice or “preseruatives’, e.g. per-
```
fuming the air and making bonfires, is present in all texts. Even more numerous are
recipes, growing in number in the seventeenth-century texts, and only absent in the
```
religious dialogue Plagves infection (1603).
```
5.4 Vernacularization and relation to other languages
All plague treatises in the category are original vernacular texts and not translations.
The texts were written by English authors and they focus solely on the epidemics
in England.
5.5 Target audience
By the seventeenth century plague was often considered a disease of the poor, because
```
they suffered from it most (Wear 2000: 281). The majority of plague treatises in the
```
corpus address the poor in some way. This is indicated directly in the title Poore mans
Category 2. Treatises on specific topics 99
```
iewel (1578), offering herbal cures, and in the title pages for Physick for the plagve and
```
Directions for the plague, which claim to be “for the Benefit and Preservation of All,
```
both Rich and Poore” (Bradwell 1636) and “Fitted for the Poorer sort” (Wharton 1665).
```
It is also implied in Certain necessary directions “With many easie Medicines of small
```
charge” (Royal College of Physicians 1636: title page). However, this was sometimes
```
only a discourse formula: Physick for the plagve does not offer any cheap remedies and
```
has adopted a negative attitude towards the poor: “Poore people (by reason of their
```
```
great want) living sluttishly, and feeding nastily and unwholsomly” (Bradwell 1636: 11).
```
However, this text is the only exception in the subcategory. The need for affordable
medicines for the poor was acknowledged in most texts. For example, three texts offer
advice for the poor and wealthy separately: “For the poore, take Aloes the waight of
sixe pence put in the pap of an Apple: and for the richer, pilles of Ruffus to be had in
```
euery Apothecaries shop” (Royal College of Physicians, Certain necessary directions,
```
```
1636: D2v). In addition to the poor, Myrrour or glasse of helth (1539) addresses “man,
```
woman, and chylde” - an often repeated phrase in the text, implying the poor. Food
and physick is the only text to address the country and the city: “And fit as well for the
```
Country, as the City” (T. D. 1665: title page), although this is generally quite common
```
```
of plague treatises (cf. Wear 2000: 280).
```
5-6 Continuity from medieval traditions versus new trends
The new natural philosophy was gaining ground over the ideas of disease transmission
and plague poison, which resulted in seeing the source of the pestilence as universal
and not localized. At the same time the emphasis on putrefaction, a medieval notion,
in identifying the sources of the plague and explaining the progress of the disease in
a body still remained. The early acknowledgement of the contagious nature of plague
```
could still be adapted to the theory of putrefaction (Wear 2000: 275-276). The prayers
```
still present in some of the texts reflect the medieval tradition of appealing to God
or the “supernatural” when encountering such a severe disease which contemporary
```
medicine could not treat (Barkai 1998: 17-18), as seen in the prayer “For those that are
```
Visited” in Food and physick: “OH Lord God, thou best Physician, both of our Souls
and Bodies, who canst bring to the Grave, and pull back again, whom thou pleasest”
```
(T. D. 1665: 15). General preventative advice derives also from medieval sources and
```
provides continuation from Middle English plague texts.
5.7. Images
There are no illustrations in the plague treatises, with the exception of an occasional
printer’s device, a portrait of the author or a decorative image on the contents page.
Therefore, plague imagery, e.g. depicting death as the danse macabre, seems to have
```
been reserved for religious texts (see Boeck! 2000).
```
