1. Chronological coverage
The chronological distribution of this category begins from 1525 and covers the rest
of the period, although the coverage is uneven. The texts from the first half of the
sixteenth century represent a continuation of the medieval manuscript tradition,
being mostly derivations of earlier works. The general boom of the latter half of the
century was the combined effect of a general increase in the number of translated
```
recipe collections and “books of secrets” (Slack 1979: 242) (here represented by the
```
```
texts of Hieronymus Braunschweig and Girolamo Ruscelli), of the appearance of
```
```
popular household recipe books such as the Treasurie of commodious conceits (1573)
```
```
and the Good huswifes iewell (1596), and of the debate for and against foreign medi-
```
```
cines (cf. the texts by Timothy Bright and Nicolas Monardes). This outpouring of new
```
remedy collections of various kinds is followed by a noticeable gap in the appearance
of new texts over the first decades of the seventeenth century, during which reprints
of late sixteenth-century books seem to have dominated the marketplace. It was in the
1650s that the printing of remedybooks and other cheaper and more popular medical
texts really took off, leading to a dramatic increase in the number of new vernacular
```
medical publications (Fissell 2007: 110; Slack 1979: 241), which is also reflected in
```
the inclusion of thirteen texts from the thirty-year period from 1633 to 1662. Printed
recipe collections and herbals also maintained their popularity well past the turn of
the eighteenth century.
2. Criteria for inclusion
This category includes texts dealing with the preparation of remedies or the therapeutic
properties of substances. These texts range from learned and authoritative compendia
of medicines - or pharmacopoeia - to household books containing medical, veteri-
nary and culinary recipes and practical tips on topics like gardening and husbandry,
and even to collections of quasi-magical remedies and charms based on folklore. In
addition to recipe collections, this category also includes books on materia medica,
such as herbals and lapidaries. These can also contain recipes, usually listed under the
substance which serves as their principal ingredient.
Although some of the more learned recipe collections and herbals were written by
university-trained physicians, this category contains a large proportion of texts written
by informally trained practitioners of medicine, empirics, quacks, or even by writers
with no real medical expertise. Many of the recipe collections are not original works
but rather derivative collections of remedies acquired by the “author” from various
sources. Some collections are even explicitly attributed to a famous practitioner or
other notable persons. Printed recipe collections were also connected to the network
Category 3. Recipe collections and materia medica 103
of oral and manuscript transmission of recipes that “was still the primary vehicle for
```
communication of medicinal advice in early modern England” (Leong & Pennell
```
```
2007: 138). Several of the recipe collections claim to be based on personal collections
```
of lords or ladies of high social standing.
Since texts placed in other categories also frequently contain recipes and infor-
mation on the properties of various materia medica, this category is partly defined
by what it omits: texts classified as RECIPE COLLECTIONS contain little or no diag-
nostic or theoretical material. The concepts of variety and collection are important
in defining this category: all texts are collections that discuss a variety of substances
or remedies for a variety of illnesses. Texts that focus solely on the properties and
preparation of individual substances or medicaments are placed in the category of
SPECIFIC THERAPEUTIC SUBSTANCES, and texts focusing on an individual ill-
ness, often including remedies, are placed in the category of SPECIFIC DISEASES.
Although the archetypal recipe collection consists strictly of a sequence of rem-
edies, some texts stretch the above definition by discussing medicines from a more
general perspective. An example of such a text is Timothy Bright’s Sufficiencie of
```
English medicines (1580), which not only provides information on the native Eng-
```
lish medicines to be used for various diseases, but also compares them to their
foreign counterparts.
3. Discourse form
The discourse form of RECIPE COLLECTIONS is one of the principal defining features of
this category. Both types of texts are often highly segmented or modular in structure,
consisting of a sequence of discrete descriptive or prescriptive passages, each focused
```
on an ailment to be cured (recipes) or a medical substance (herbals and lapidaries). The
```
organization of these discrete passages varies in both recipe collections and herbals.
Some follow a multi-tiered organization, making primary divisions according to the
```
general type of substance (trees, herbs, animal parts, etc.) or disease (fevers, ulcers,
```
```
aches, etc.) and then organizing the material within these groups either alphabetically
```
or based on some other rationale. Some recipe collections, especially earlier ones like
```
the Treasure ofpore men (1526), still follow a medieval pattern of textual organization
```
according to the site of the ailment, beginning from the head and ending up with the
feet. By contrast, other texts present their material in a strictly alphabetical order, like
```
Owen Wood's Alphabetical book ofphysicall secrets (1639).
```
The individual recipe segments that make up most of the recipe collections also
tend to be more or less formulaic, although the exact formula followed by each indi-
vidual collection varies. Some collections employ quite technical and abrupt expres-
sions with frequent abbreviations, such as the learned Pharmacopoeia Bateana:
