The dialogue form, which is common in other categories, is not used for communicat-
ing remedies. The closest analogue to this form is found in learned pharmacopoeias
```
translated from Latin, such as Salmon’s Pharmacopoeia Bateana (1700) and Nicholas
```
```
Culpeper’s London dispensatory (1649), where the translator has inserted comments
```
on the original text.
In addition to purely instructive recipe collections and herbals, this category also
includes some more argumentative texts, such as the above-mentioned Sufficiencie of
```
English medicines (1580), which embeds the description of medical properties of plants
```
into an argumentative framework. Case reports as such are not a part of the repertoire
of recipe collections, although we may occasionally find brief references to successful
cures, proving the efficacy of a recipe.
4. Vernacularization and relation to other languages
Since there was already an extensive tradition of vernacular manuscript recipe collec-
tions in the later Middle Ages, it is not surprising that most of the recipe collections
included in the corpus are original vernacular compositions. This is especially true of
the more popular household recipe collections, whose closest affiliation is most likely
with the medieval manuscript tradition and the informal oral and manuscript circu-
106 Ville Marttila
lation of recipes among friends and relatives. Only a third of the recipe collections
```
are translations; six are translated from Latin and one each from French (Charas),
```
```
German (Braunschweig), Spanish (Monardes) and Italian via French (Ruscelli).
```
The translations found in this category are mostly either popular international
```
bestsellers like the Secretes ofAlexis of Piemovnt (1562), originally published in Italian
```
and later published in more than a hundred editions in almost all European languages,
or more learned recipe collections such as the London dispensatory or the Pharmaco-
poeia Bateana, which were both translated from Latin originals. While the motives for
publishing a popular foreign work in English were probably economic, the translators
of learned recipe collections often appealed to more noble causes. Culpeper writes in
his preface that he translated the work for the benefit of Englishmen who “are led by
```
the noses (worse than beasts, as though oppression had already made them mad) by a
```
```
company of proud, insulting, domineering Doctors” (London dispensatory, 1649: Alv).
```
On the other hand, revealing the secrets of learned medicine to ignorant laymen and
greedy charlatans was severely disapproved of by the learned community, and Cul-
peper acknowledges this at the end of his catalogue of simples:
```
(5) I willingly omited the vertues of many of them, partly because I would not have
```
the Book too big, partly because they are not easily gotten and many of the
operations I buried in silence for fear knaves should put them in practice to do
```
mischief: Remembring a speech once in a Sermon of Bishop Latimers, ] could
```
```
(saith he) reprove other sins from this text, but 1 wil not; for fear you knowing
```
```
what they be, should practise them. (Culpeper, London dispensatory, 1649: 77)
```
Rather shrewdly, he also allays the apothecaries’ fears of losing their business by
pointing out that he was essentially advertising their services:
```
(6) As for Apothecaries they have least reason of all to complain, because it tends
```
to the advancement of their trade, If they have not wit enough to know, that
private men cannot make up most of these compositions themselves, but
knowing the vertues of ... them, will resort the more to them for physick, they
deserve the name of a company of Dunces.
```
(Culpeper, London dispensatory, 1649: A2v)
```
In the case of herbals, the situation is somewhat different, as half of the texts included
in the corpus are translations from foreign originals. The vernacular tradition is repre-
```
sented by the first printed herbal in English, Newe mater (1525), which combines parts
```
```
from many medieval English herbals, William Langham's Garden of health (1597) and
```
```
John Pechey’s Herbal of physical plants (1694). Translated herbals include the Grete
```
```
herball (1526), which is an English translation of the French herbal Le Grant Herbier,
```
```
the Names of herbes (1548) which is an English version of William Turner’s Latin
```
Libellus de re herbaria novus published in 1538, and Gerard’s influential Generall his-
```
torie of plantes (1633). Gerard’s herbal is an especially interesting work: it is based
```
Category 3. Recipe collections and materia medica 107
on an earlier unfinished translation of Rembert Dodoens’s Latin herbal, which was
then commented on and added to by Gerard, and further enlarged and amended by
Thomas Johnson for its second edition, which serves as the source of the corpus text.
5. Target audience
While remedybooks have traditionally been associated with the most popular end of
the continuum from popular to learned medicine, they can rightly be seen as spanning
the whole spectrum and constituting a shared material culture between lay people
```
and medical practitioners (Wear 2000: 40, 103). Although the most likely audience for
```
medical texts in general in the sixteenth century seems to have been the social elite,
remedybooks - being cheap enough and available in sufficient quantity - were rather
more accessible and would most likely have been within the reach of “apothecaries and
others at the lower levels of medical practice’, and by the end of the sixteenth century
```
also some yeomen and tradesmen, especially in London (Slack 1979: 261). From the
```
seventeenth century we have more information about the target audience, since by that
time it had become customary to include information about the intended audience in
```
the preface or even on the title page of the book (Fissell 2007: 111), which also served
```
a crucial advertising function:
```
(7) Collected for the benefit, most especially of House-holders in the Country, who
```
are either farre remote, or else not able to entertaine a Learned Physician: as
likewise for the help of such Ladies and Gentle-women, who of charity labour
```
to doe good. (Wood, Alphabetical book, 1639: title page)
```
Targeting householders and gentlewomen as readers of recipe collections is not sur-
prising, since the private household was the primary arena for medical treatment in
```
the pre-modern era (Leong & Pennell 2007: 134), and the employment of “kitchen
```
medicine” almost always preceded the intervention of an outside medical practitio-
```
ner. Slack (1979: 260) has pointed out that remedy collections were used especially by
```
women, both by the housewife within her own family and by women who visited and
cared for their sick friends and neighbours,
Since remedybooks were at the more “voluminous” end of the spectrum of
medical literature, they had a potentially wider readership than other categories of
```
medical texts, printed in smaller quantities (Slack 1979: 258). The potential readership
```
of remedybooks was not limited to the capital and other large cities, since the habit
of householders to collect private manuscript collections of remedies also made
them a potential audience for printed collections. Neither was the target audience
of vernacular recipe collections necessarily restricted to medical laypeople. Not all
```
medical professionals (physicians, apothecaries, surgeons, etc.) were fluent in Latin
```
and they would have found vernacular texts very useful. This was the rationale given
108 Ville Marttila
by William Salmon in his preface to his translation of the Pharmacopoeia Bateana,
```
published “for the Benefit of all the Lovers of this kind of Learning” (p. A4v), with
```
the purpose of promoting equality between students of medicine, whether “Vulgar”
or Latinate:
```
(8) It is my Opinion, that the Art of Physick is not any particular Mans or
```
```
Societies proper Right, more than anothers; but that every Man has an equal
```
share in the same. But ‘tis like Gold and Silver, he that wins it, or takes pains
for it, shall have it. And as in one, every Man has a Right to study Physick if
```
he pleases; and having one made himself Master of the Knowledge of it, has as
```
```
great a Right to use it as we. (Salmon, Pharmacopoeia Bateana, 1700: A5v)
```
In practice, both the target audiences and actual readerships of vernacular recipe
collections were often mixed, as both laypeople and medical professionals appar-
```
ently read works which were intended for the other group (Wear 2000: 40-41; Slack
```
```
1979: 256-257). An interesting example of this is provided by the personal papers
```
```
of Elizabeth Freke (1671-1714) — best known for her surviving memoirs - which
```
contain extensive reading notes from such professionally oriented texts as John
Gerard’s herbal, Nicholas Culpeper’s School of physick, Moyse Charas’s and George
Bate’s pharmacopoeias, and Culpeper’s translation of the Pharmacopoeia Londinensis
```
(Leong 2008: 150-151).
```
6. Continuity from medieval traditions versus new trends
The printed remedybook was a direct descendant of the medieval tradition of manu-
script recipe collections and there are close similarities between them, especially in
```
structural terms (Fissell 2007: 116-117). Both were practically oriented and had very
```
little explanation in terms of medical theory, focusing on listing practical remedies
for various illnesses. The remedy tradition was also inherently conservative, with the
medieval Galenic theory of medicine forming the basis for most early modern rem-
edy collections. This should not come as a surprise, since early collections were often
either printed versions of medieval texts like Roger Bacon's text on Waters artyfycialles
```
(1550) or derivative works based on the earlier tradition, and their authors were not
```
```
necessarily medical professionals themselves (Slack 1979: 252-253).
```
The late sixteenth century also saw the introduction of new remedies, both from
the New World and the Old. New medicinal plants such as tobacco, coca and sassafras
were being introduced from America and were initially hailed as miraculous panaceas
```
in treatises extolling their virtues (see spECIFIC THERAPEUTIC SUBSTANCES), but gradu-
```
ally became a part of the more general pharmacopoeia. These new medicines were not,
however, universally accepted: many, like Bright in his Sufficiencie of English medicines
```
(1580), considered them not only unnecessarily expensive, but also foreign to the
```
Category 3. Recipe collections and materia medica 109
English complexion. Also classical medicinal plants, such as balsam, myrrh, petroseli-
```
num and rhubarb, along with laudanum (opium), were being rediscovered and intro-
```
duced into Western Europe. Towards the end of the seventeenth century herbals also
became more botanical in orientation, and in the later herbals the description of the
medical virtues of plants is clearly subsidiary to the physical description of the plants.
The rise of Paracelsianism and iatrochemistry in the seventeenth century also
brought with it a host of chemical remedies, many of which were based on the Para-
```
celsian basic principles of salt, sulphur and mercury (Pagel 1958: 82-89), Although
```
these chemical remedies were the subject of great controversy and were condemned
by many practitioners, many of them were gradually accepted and integrated into
the pharmacopoeias alongside the traditional Galenic medicines. For example, the
```
London dispensatory (1649) includes a separate section of chemical remedies and the
```
```
Royal pharmacopoea (1678) is divided into two parts of equal length between Galenic
```
and chemical remedies.
7. Images
Apart from purely decorative images, such as enlarged and decorated capitals, deco-
rative borders and generic title page illustrations, recipe collections contain virtually
no illustrations, and even these kinds of decorative features are not very numerous.
Early Modern English herbals are also surprisingly plain in appearance and most of
them contain no illustrations of plants whatsoever. Of the fifteenth-century herb-
```
als, only the anonymous Grete herball (1526) contains images of the various plants
```
described, but even these are very conventional and largely iconic instead of being
accurate depictions of the plants. Rather curiously, the Grete herball also contains an
illustration of the human skeleton with its bones named, placed in between its table
of contents and the text itself. However, it is not until the seventeenth century and
```
Gerard’s Generall historie of plantes (1633) that we see representative artistic illustra-
```
tions of plants that can be considered at least reasonably accurate depictions of their
physical properties.
