2. Criteria for inclusion
Regimens and health guides focus on hygiene, or the conservation of health, rather
```
than on therapeutics (the treatment of illness). The distinction between the two was
```
made very clear by writers of regimen texts, for therapeutics was firmly within the
domain of learned physicians, and thus should not be available to lay people. The
prevention of illness, on the other hand, was something people could influence them-
selves by their living habits. Hence regimens and health guides give advice on diet
— including the qualities of different foodstuffs and drinks — as well as on various
aspects of lifestyle. Sir Thomas Elyot, lexicographer and humanist, emphasizes in his
```
Castel of helth (1541) that he is not infringing in the domain of physicians but rather
```
helping them:
```
(1)... men and women redinge this warke, and obseruinge the counsayles therin,
```
shulde adapte therby their bodies, to receyue more sure remedy by the medi-
cines prepared by good phisitions in da~gerous syckenesses, they kepynge good
dyet, and infourmynge diligently the same phisitions, of y=e= maner of their
```
affectes, passions, and sensible tokens. (Elyot, Castel of helth, 1541: 94v)
```
However, in practice the distinction between prevention and treatment of illness was
blurred in health guides, for they had the same theoretical foundation. The physician
```
Philip Moore outlined the contents of his treatise Hope of Health (1565) in the follow-
```
ing manner:
```
(2) In this treatise you shall find: Firste, what thynges are necessarie to bee knowen,
```
for the preseruacion and mainteinaunce of healthe. Secondarily, what thynges
are to bee obserued, concernying thyne ordinarie diette, in sunderie meates to
auoyde sickenesse. Thirdlie, the vse of a gardein, and the natures of sunderie
herbes. Fowerthlie, the declaracion of sickenes, and the commodities of
medicines. Last of all, you shall finde certain rules of Astronomie, whereof the
```
moste part are annexed vnto Phisicke: ... (Moore, Hope of health, 1565: *3r-v)
```
Though Moore is careful to claim that his aim is the “preseruacion and maintein-
aunce of healthe’, his inclusion of topics such as astrology and humoral theory
seems to cross over into learned medicine. Many of the texts in this category include
astrological information, about for example the influence on man of the moon and
the twelve signs of the zodiac at various times of the year and month. This kind of
information was important for determining the right time for phlebotomy, which
```
was practised for both prevention and treatment of illness (see SPECIFIC METHODS),
```
Regimens and health guides often also include discussion of humoral theory and the
four complexions in order to give more specific information on the effects of the six
```
non-naturals (air, food and drink, sleep and waking, movement and rest, retention and
```
```
evacuation, which included sexual activity, and passions of the soul or emotions) on
```
```
various complexions; texts focusing on these theoretical aspects are found in GENERAL
```
