TREATISES. Moreover, listing remedies for various illnesses further blurred the distinc-
tion between hygiene and therapeutics.
Throughout the period, advice on health often includes a moralizing component.
Especially recommendations of temperance, found already in the ancient authoritative
texts quoted in regimens, also included a religious component. Intemperance led net
only to illness and disease, but also to moral corruption:
```
(3)... and certainly says our wise man, most that have addicted themselves to
```
variety, extravagancy and excess, have thereby either loaded themselves with
```
new cares, or contracted new vices; and so become obnoxious to various and
```
great troubles, and frequently commit Rapines, Cheats, violating Justice, Faith,
and Friendship, and many times precipitate themselves into grievous Diseases,
```
losses and disparagements; which by Frugality, Temperance and Sobriety they
```
```
might have avoided: ... (Cock, Kitchin-physick, 1676: 76-77)
```
