4. Vernacularization and relation to other languages
Most of the earliest sixteenth-century regimen texts were translations or adaptations of
medieval Latin texts, many of which were attributed to ancient or medieval authorities
such as Aristotle, Ptolemy, Joannes de Mediolano or the school of Salerno. The first
```
original vernacular text in the corpus is Elyot’s Castel of helth (1541), but from then on
```
original texts in the vernacular dominate. There are still some translations, but they are
of works by contemporary continental authors such as Guglielmo Gratarolo or John
```
Ghesel; the only English author whose text has been translated from Latin is Francis
```
```
Bacon (Historie of life and death, 1638). We have also included another text by Francis
```
```
Bacon in this category, Of regiment of health (1625), which is written in the vernacular.
```
Latin is the most commonly translated language, but there are a few texts translated
from French. Interestingly, in all the cases French is not the original language of the
```
text; most often the French text is a translation from Latin, but one text was originally
```
written in Dutch.
The majority of the regimens and health guides in the corpus were, however, writ-
```
ten in the vernacular by English authors, most of them physicians (though there is
```
```
room for a hatter as well, Thomas Tryon). Along with Sir Thomas Elyot, one of the
```
most noteworthy of these authors was the physician Andrew Boorde, of whose texts
```
three are included in the corpus: Dyetary of helth (1542), Breuiary of helthe (1547) and
```
```
Boke for to lerne a man (15502). Many of the corpus texts went through several print-
```
```
ings, which indicates their popularity; for example the anonymous Compost of Ptho-
```
```
lomeus (1540) was reprinted at least five times between 1530 and 1562 and yet again in
```
```
1632, and Castel of helth (1541) was printed no less than sixteen times before the close
```
of the sixteenth century.
5. Target audience
Regimens and health guides were aimed primarily at the middling and upper levels of
society, not at the general population, even when authors made such claims. The buy-
ers of these books were literate people with enough money to spend on ensuring their
```
health by following the advice in the books; Andrew Wear calls them the “luxury end of
```
```
medicine” (2000: 154). Those considered to be most at risk of illness were idle or seden-
```
tary inhabitants of cities, such as the students and magistrates addressed in Guglielmo
```
Gratarolos Health of magistrates and studentes (1574). The air in cities was considered
```
less healthy than in the countryside, and the lack of physical labour further increased
```
the risk of illness; labourers in the countryside thus did not need any advice on their
```
health. Idleness and gluttony were sins the well-off were more likely to be guilty of
than workers. Furthermore, the exercises recommended in health guides - for example
Category 4. Regimens and health guides 117
tennis, dancing, horse-riding as well as running — indicate that the readers of these texts
```
came from the middling and upper levels (Wear 2000: 159-160).
```
Andrew Boorde's instructions on building a house show that he had a specific
audience in mind. According to him, a man’s house should be built in a place with
wood, water, and fresh air, with a “prospecte to and fro the place, [that is] pleasaunt,
fayre, and good to the iye, to behold the woddes, the waters, the feldes, the vales the
hylles, & the playne grounde”. The house should have a multitude of chambers, a but-
tery, a bakery, a chapel, a stable, and various other outhouses. Boorde also recom-
mends that the house
```
(9) haue an orecherde of sondrye fruytes, but it is more co~modyous to haue a
```
fayre gardyn repleatyd with herbes of aromatyke and redole~t sauoures, in the
gardyn maye be a poole or two for fysshe, yf the pooles be clene kept. Also a
parke repletyd with dere and conys, is a necessary and a pleasaunt thynge to be
anexed to a mansyon. A doue howse also is a necessary thinge aboute a
```
mansyon place. (Boorde, Boke for to lerne a man, 1550?: A2r-B3v)
```
Clearly such a house was not within the reach of a regular farm labourer.
The readers of these books were not assumed to have specialized medical knowl-
edge, though references to authorities or Latin terms are not completely absent.
Potentially unfamiliar terms are often accompanied by English translations, but it
is more usual to explain everything in simple lay terms. Regimens thus attempt to give
practical and down-to-earth instructions on maintaining health. The practice of laying
out the theoretical justifications for the advice educated lay people with the basic con-
cepts of learned medicine, which led to a more unified medical culture in which “the
world and everything in it was seen through medical spectacles as an organic whole”
```
(Wear 2000: 154).
```
6. Continuity from medieval traditions versus new trends
There were no significant changes in regimens and health guides in this period — the
basic tenets for maintaining health remained the same as they were in the Middle
Ages. The first half of the sixteenth century saw the publication of several medieval
health guides, some of which had their roots already in antiquity, but early mod-
ern authors writing original texts founded their advice on the same assumptions as
medieval and ancient writers. The reason for this continuity probably lies in the slow
change in people's lifestyles: though urbanization was increasing, the countryside
was still seen as the healthier environment. The healthiness of certain foods, envi-
ronments and habits such as temperance was not based solely on learned medicine
but had been proven by long tradition, and thus the basic values embodied in health
advice remained unchallenged. Even when belief in the humoral system declined after
n8 Carla Suhr
the mid-seventeenth century, the advice given in regimens and health guides did not
```
change (Wear 2000: 155, 208-209).
```
7- Images
Regimens and health guides rarely included illustrations or tables, and on the whole
they are rather austere, with decorations usually limited to distinctive initial letters.
```
In fact, only Bullein’s Gouernement of health (1595) and Cock’s Kitchin-physick (1676)
```
have illustrations that pertain to the topic at hand: Bullein includes an anatomical
figure showing the astrological signs influencing the various parts of the body to visu
alize when to bleed specific veins, whereas Cock’s text has an illustration of a stove,
as he discusses bathing and stoving as part of a healthy regime. One text has purely
```
decorative images. Compost of Ptholomeus (1540) has an illustration of a man on the
```
title page and preceding the prologue, both identified as the alleged author Ptolemy. In
addition, there is an elaborate printer's device, which can be found in a few other texts
as well. Even though the potential buyers of regimens and health guides were most
likely people with money to spare, the increase in book price that woodcut illustra-
tions and especially copper engravings entailed perhaps outweighed the benefits of
having illustrations.
Two texts that include astrological information also have relevant tables. Philip
```
Moore's Hope of health (1565) includes monthly charts indicating the times of sunrise
```
and sunset and the length of days and nights, as well as a table and a figure by which
readers could calculate what sign the moon is in. James Manning’s Complexions castle
```
(1604) has a table showing the diagnoses of humoral sicknesses based on the astro-
```
logical properties of the day of the week when the patient falls sick. However, as with
illustrations, visual aids of this type are extremely rare.
