1. Chronological coverage
Surgical and anatomical texts fall on the timeline quite evenly from 1525 onwards.
Surgery was a major branch of medical writing from the very beginning. The earliest
120 Jukka Tyrkké
printed books in this category drew heavily on the continental, as well as the Latin,
tradition. Notably, as a result of the composition of the respective readerships, exten-
sive surgical treatises began to appear in the vernacular earlier than similar books did
in physick. There are no significant gaps along the EMEMT timeline when it comes to
surgical works.
2. Criteria for inclusion
‘The texts in this category form one of the most strongly thematic collections of texts
in the corpus. They originate from the distinct tradition of surgical writing, and the
authors or editors are almost invariably surgeons established in the profession. In
reflection of the true nature of the textual field, the proportion of texts originating in
continental Europe is higher than in any other category in EMEMT.
Until the mid seventeenth century at least, surgery was considered a branch
```
of medicine manifestly apart from physick (see, e.g. Furdell 2002: 19-21). While
```
the latter was primarily concerned, in the first instance, with humoral explana-
tions of physiological processes, and later with a variety of new paradigms ranging
from astromedicine to iatrochemistry, the surgeons’ craft extended over all ailments
believed to have a physical cause. The early modern barber-surgeon was not a phy-
sician with a specialism in surgery, but rather a medical craftsman with an entirely
different background and career path. Although the division between physicians and
```
surgeons was not quite as wide as it is sometimes portrayed (see Nutton 1985: 75),
```
the two professions did form two distinct - and, at times, clashing — factions of
medical care.
Surgeons in England were not trained at universities but through apprentice-
```
ship (see Wear 2000: 217-219). Some surgeons sought education at continental
```
universities such as Bologna and Montpellier, where surgery enjoyed a much higher
prestige than back home. Surgical texts fell roughly into two admittedly overlap-
ping main types: those dealing with surgical theory and technique, and those
focused on anatomy. Among the former we can count all works which attempt to
cover the whole professional field of surgery, as well as those treating a specific field
of surgical practice. The latter consists of works devoted to descriptive anatomy.
Books of both types are included in EMEMT in equal measure. In the early modern
period, the craft of surgery also included the preparation and use of topical medica-
ments. Consequently, many of the texts in this category include recipes, and such
texts have been deemed to be surgical in nature unless the entire extract consists
only of recipes, in which case the text belongs to the category RECIPE COLLECTIONS
```
(see above).
```
