3. Discourse form
Early modern surgical writing was largely practical in orientation. The main pur-
pose of a text was to provide basic information about the human anatomy and to
instruct the surgeon in practical methods of treating trauma. Because the surgical
student did not have the same grounding in natural philosophy as the student in
physic, much of the theoretical content was either omitted or presented from a more
practical perspective.
The didactic slant of surgical writing comes through consistently. The books fre-
```
quently begin with a discussion of the necessary qualities of a good surgeon; physi-
```
cal strength and manual dexterity are usually praised along with mental acumen and
```
resilience. The physician William Bullein’s Bulleins bulwarke (1562) begins with the
```
following description:
```
(1) HE must begin first in youth with good learning, & excercise in this noble art,
```
he also must be clenly, nimble handed, sharpe sighted, prignant witted, bolde
spirited, clenly apparailed, pitefull harted, but not womenly affeccionated: to
wepe or trimble, whe~ he seeth broken bones, or bloodie woundes, neither
muste he geue place to the crie of his sore paciente, for softe Chyrurgians
```
maketh fowle sores. {Bullein, Bulleins bulwarke, 1562: 1)
```
Bullein’s text is also notable for introducing the mimetic dialogue format into ver-
```
nacular medical writing (see Taavitsainen & Nevanlinna 1999; 153). Bullein’s contem-
```
