```
more texts in the category: Quydos questions (1579), a French surgical treatise trans-
```
```
lated by Robert Copland and revised by George Baker; Thomas Gale's Institution of a
```
```
chirurgian (1563); and Peter Lowe’s Whole art of chyrvrgerie (1612).
```
In surgical works as in other early modern medical texts, the enumerative and
ordered pattern of presentation frequently dominates. The extent of Latin terminology
is particularly marked in anatomical works, with many texts devoting most attention
to the naming of body parts and physiological processes. Marginal comments are used
frequently, often for the purpose of marking specific sections of the text or to give ref-
```
erences to classical sources, as in the aforementioned Whole art of chyrvrgerie (1612).
```
Surgical writers allude to both classical and contemporary sources at a higher rate
than most other early modern medical authors. The discursive topos of the body as a
```
“microcosmos” was common to early modern anatomy; the term is found in the title
```
of three books in this category.
The surgeon’s realm also extended to topical remedies, and consequently many
