4. Vernacularization and relation to other languages
Early surgical works were mostly translations. Most were from Latin, but owing to the
close relations between English and continental surgeons, a substantial number were
also translated from contemporary vernacular languages — unlike in the other catego-
```
ries. Continental authors in the category include French (Chauliac, Guillemeau, Paré),
```
```
Italian (de Vigo, Fioravanti), and Dutch (Barbette) surgeons, among others.
```
Vernacular translations were in much greater demand among surgeons than phy-
sicians because the education of the latter required at least some proficiency in Latin.
Latinate surgeons were the exception, and those that did read Latin almost invariably
```
belonged to the highest stratum of the profession (see Pelling & Webster 1979; 177;
```
```
Wear 2000: 218). The issue of vernacularization became a point of some contention
```
Category 5. Surgical and anatomical treatises 123
between the Company of Barber-Surgeons and the College of Physicians in the late
sixteenth century when the top surgeons began to systematically produce English
```
translations of authors like Lanfranc and Galen (see Nutton 1985: 98). Surgeons were
```
accused of endangering the livelihoods of both professions by revealing medical secrets
to laymen, a point which in actual fact concerned them as much if not more than it did
the physicians. This concern resonated with the copious number of popular medical
books, the title pages of which promise the secrets of the Queen’s closet or the ability
to act as one’s own doctor.
Latin and Greek terminology features in surgical texts in more or less equal mea-
sure to vernacular books of physick. Glossaries explaining hard words are found in
```
several books, including de Vigo’s Most excellent workes of chirurgerye (1543) and
```
```
Woodall’s Svrgions mate (1617).
```
5. Target audience
The texts in this category were written primarily for members of the surgical commu-
nity and, perhaps in particular, to apprentices. Because surgeons did not receive formal
education apart from some classes organized by the Company of Barber-Surgeons,
the need for comprehensive written reference works was particularly great. Surgeons
frequently state in the preliminaries that a given book was written in English for the
benefit of younger colleagues who cannot read Latin, but often go on to emphasize
that the intention was not to make the knowledge available to those outside the pro-
fession. Indeed, surgeons frequently appear particularly keen to draw a line between
```
proper medical professionals - physicians and themselves - and charlatans (see e.g.
```
```
Wear 2000: 220).
```
The intended audience of surgical writing is reflected in the predominantly
instructive style employed by the authors. Anatomical descriptions often dominate the
longer treatises, giving the kind of detailed information about the body that only pro-
fessional audiences could benefit from. Although the main readership of anatomical
treatises was undoubtedly surgeons, physicians are likely to have also taken an interest.
In general, surgical treatises make few concessions to the non-professional reader.
Operative instructions focus on diagnosis and practical methodology. Surgical
instruments are described in detail, and procedural descriptions of surgical techniques
are frequently provided. In the excerpt below, Thomas Gale describes how to diagnose
