6. Continuity from medieval traditions versus new trends
Surgical texts were a part of the English vernacular tradition of medical writing long
before the printing press, with extant manuscript editions including texts by Chauliac,
Lanfranc, and Mondeville, among others. Vernacular translations of Galen in par-
ticular helped form common ground between surgical literature and sources par-
tially shared with physicians. The scholastic inheritance is evident in surgical treatises
well into the seventeenth century, although in many ways the surgeons’ reliance on
natural philosophy was less restrictive than was the case with physicians. References
to classical authors, already mentioned above, attest to the persisting influence of
scholastic knowledge.
Category 5. Surgical and anatomical treatises 125
Many of the first printed surgical texts were based on Middle English manuscripts,
which in turn tended to have Latin origins. The concept of authorship was still very
much in its infancy in the sixteenth century, and texts often underwent very compli-
cated and difficult-to-trace patterns of transmission. A prime example is the case of
```
Compendiosa totius anatomie delineatio (1553), a book conventionally attributed to
```
the printer Thomas Geminus. The English version, included in EMEMT, followed two
Latin editions printed in England. Ostensibly an edition of Vesaliuss groundbreak-
```
ing De humani corporis fabrica (1543), the text in fact bears little resemblance to the
```
Latin original. The text was adapted by the schoolmaster Nicholas Udall from Thomas
```
Vicary's Anatomie of the bodie of man (1548) - itself based on a Middle English manu-
```
script written by Henry de Mondeville.
The major innovation of the early modern period was the printing of compre-
hensive anatomies based on empirical observation. Some of these were illustrated, but
many more relied on the power of the word to describe the appearance and func-
tions of internal organs with as much precision as possible. The following excerpt from
```
William Harvey's Anatomical exercises (1653) describes the structures of the heart:
```
```
(6) The first touch and union of the vena cava with the arteria venosa, which
```
comesto passe before the the vena cava opens it self into the right ventricle of
the hart, or sends out the Coronal vein, a little above its outgoing from the liver,
displaysunto us its orifice side-ways, that is to say, a hole, wide and large, of a
```
oval figure. (Harvey, Anatomical exercises, 1653: 29)
```
7. Images
For obvious reasons, surgical and anatomical works were some of the most important
medical context for the use of woodcut and bronze engraved illustrations. Expositions
on surgical instruments, operative methods, and anatomical structures all benefit
greatly from accompanying illustrations. On the other hand, high quality illustrations
were difficult and expensive to produce. Images ranged from illustrated title pages
and individual semi decorative flourishes to extensive collections of plates and foldout
sheets. Diagrams and tabular charts are rare.
The highlight of sixteenth-century medical illustration was naturally Andreas
```
Vesalius’s aforementioned De humani corporis fabrica (1543). Printed in Basel, the
```
book was to begin a revolution in medical printing. At a time when illustrations in
printed books were of a fairly low quality, Vesalius's exquisite folio sized woodcuts
quickly gained fame for their quality and attention to detail. It had repercussions in
England as well. Although the illustrations in the English version produced in 1553 by
Thomas Geminus are not of the same standard, they went far and beyond what was
126 Jukka Tyrkko
typical at the time. A comparison of Geminus’s illustrations with those in Hieronymus
```
Braunschweig’s Handy warke of surgeri (1525), both in the EMEMT image gallery,
```
reveals the dramatic difference in quality over a timespan of less than thirty years.
The paratextual use of images as genuine illustrations of topics discussed in the text
can be found in several texts. The detailed anatomical illustrations in Helkiah Crooke's
```
Mikrokosmografia (1615) come with a key naming each structure in the respective
```
engraving. In general, the early modern period saw medical illustrations develop from
largely decorative flourishes into pragmatically grounded elements of the text.
