6. Continuity versus new trends
The Royal Society provided a forum where experiences from medical practice could
be linked with the domain of experimental research. Medical research was cumula-
tive to some degree, as many articles address queries made in earlier issues. However,
```
as Porter (1989: 279, 283) points out, the society did not have a systematic research
```
agenda, and articles published in the PT were extremely miscellaneous and included
descriptions of medical curiosities and panaceas. Moreover, clinical practice was only
partially influenced by the Society, as natural philosophers especially on the continent
considered scientific work and clinical practice to be two separate activities, and saw
```
the latter as merely a means of providing income (Hall 1971: 122-123). But even so, the
```
PT played an important role in the development of medicine in the seventeenth cen-
tury. Besides the few trivial and uninformed articles, the PT published a great number
```
of learned texts devoted to basic science (Hall 1971: 120). What is more, the Society
```
encouraged a new style of clinical practice incorporating systematic observation and
```
recording (Porter 1989: 278).
