The APPENDIX contains 32 texts with some 203,382 words. These texts treat medicine
as a social phenomenon, taking a point of view other than that of analysing and treat-
ing diseases. They form a heterogeneous group that does not aim at representativeness.
The reason why we have included these texts in the corpus is to display the spectrum of
texts at the fringes of medical writing, representing the fuzzy edges of the field. At the
same time, some lines of development emerge. Texts in this category demonstrate the
wide social context of medical writing, and show that medical topics are prominently
discussed also in non-medical discourse.
A diversity of topics and discourse forms is connected with medical issues in early
modern England. Theoretical treatises contemplating medicine as a science and the
nature and limits of knowledge are included together with discussions on medicine as
a profession and medical ethics. Religious and moral texts, often polemical, pertain-
ing to medicine and its practitioners form one subgroup. Another group shows how
changing views of natural philosophy and the discoveries in the New World affected
some medical fields. Some texts cross over the border to literary works. They reflect
the circumstances of life at the time of pestilence, or display elaborate ways of com-
municating medical knowledge. Finally, the medical texts excerpted from almanacs
give an idea of the kind of medical information available to the masses at large in the
early modern period.
The following survey casts spotlights in various directions, and thus the struc-
ture of this section is different from the descriptions of categories from one to six.
Discourse forms, continuation from medieval practices and other topics found in
previous category descriptions are discussed whenever pertinent.
