5. Almanacs
Prognostications and almanac lore form an important part of the APPENDIx. Alma-
nacs were among the cheapest publications of this period, and they were bought by
```
all strata of society; there was a range of almanacs that catered to everyone (Curth
```
```
2007: 84-5). The material is focused on some particular years to give a better idea of
```
the scope of this kind of literature, which consists of short and miscellaneous pieces
of text on a variety of topics such as agriculture, animal husbandry, weights and mea-
```
sures and medical advice as well as calendars (Curth 2007: 44). For example, the year
```
```
1649 is represented by prognostications in four almanacs (by Joseph Chamberlaine,
```
Medicine in society 145
```
William Dade, John Swallow and John White); another collection of four almanacs
```
included in the apPENDIx is from the period 1688-1694.
Medical components typically specify the “fittest times to take Physick by Pur-
gations’, but they also include moon prognostications, homo signorum texts, various
kinds of nativities and seasonal rules. These texts provide continuation from medieval
```
treatises (see Taavitsainen 1988), and similar texts of the sixteenth century are included
```
in REGIMENS. Medical components in almanacs are short, and thus their extracts have
been placed in the apPENDIx. When looked at as a whole, however, the APPENDIX texts
can tell a great deal about early modern medical practices of the general public.
Rules for the right timing of medical actions, both preventative and curative, were
important aids for everyday life, and thus they were often also included in both alma-
nacs and regimens and health guides. For example the following is a hybrid combining
‘ a moon prognostication with homo signorum advice:
