6. Conclusion
The notion of science includes the way in which we perceive and understand natural
```
phenomena and our world; all this underwent changes at the end of the early modern
```
period. The apPENDIX contains a variety of texts at the fuzzy edges of medical writing
from polemical pamphlets to literary works, and thus the texts in the category map
some of the areas of overlap with different fields but also the main lines of develop-
ment of the medical field. The changing early modern world is reflected in the texts
discussing man’s limitations regarding science but also in the polemical and liter-
ary texts concerned with medical ethics and other social issues of medicine as well
as the texts describing the New World. Alchemical and astrological texts show how
```
medical fields move from the core of medicine towards its periphery; as chemistry
```
and astronomy gradually became separate sciences, their predecessors, alchemy and
astrology, lost their status as branches of medicine. Astrology is still present in the
medical advice found in popular almanacs throughout the early modern period, but
alongside traditional moon prognostications appear new marketing strategies of the
changing commercial world: advertisements for medicines and medical services. Texts
in the APPENDIX reflect all these changes from another point of view than the other
categories, and are therefore important for completing the picture of Early Modern
English medical writing.
