Texts included in EMEMT have served as research material in studies by members
of the Scientific Thought-styles project since the late 1990s. In the early phases of the
project, small datasets, sometimes only a few texts, were explored in mainly qualitative
studies or to provide continuity to studies of Middle English medical writing based on
MEMT. With the gradual growth of the material, quantitative approaches and system-
atic explorations of the whole EMEMT corpus or its individual text categories became
possible. The early studies provided valuable information about the text population
```
and contributed to the further planning of the corpus (see e.g. Taavitsainen 1999),
```
while later studies also served as quantitative pilot studies or for testing particular
```
aspects of the corpus (see the chapter by Lehto, Oinonen and Pahta). These studies
```
have already changed the earlier view of the medical register in Early Modern English,
showing that is was more diverse than was previously assumed.
Three chapters are included in this part. They illustrate the research based on
EMEMT, and the new knowledge that has been obtained using it. At the same time, they
also give examples of the ways in which corpus linguistic methods can be used to answer
research questions in different subfields of historical language analysis. Two studies,
based on the final pre-release version of EMEMT, are published here for the first time.
The first chapter, “Explorations through Early Modern English Medical Texts:
Charting changes in medical discourse and scientific thinking” by Anu Lehto, Raisa
Oinonen and Paivi Pahta, presents a survey of EMEMT-based research published by
the project members. The chapter offers a glimpse on the variety of uses for the cor-
pus, and summarizes the key findings based on it. Most studies are diachronic, focus-
ing on continuity and change in medical writings over time, often relating them to
language-external continuities and changes in the domain of medicine. Some stud-
ies compare the findings from EMEMT with results from MEMT for a broader dia-
chronic line, while others make use of some other electronic corpora or reference tools
for comparison.
The second chapter, “Sign terms in specific medical genres in early modern medi-
cal texts” by Jukka Tyrkké, illustrates the interdisciplinary approach to the history of
medical writing which EMEMT facilitates. Tyrkk6 examines a lexical field that occupies
150 Paivi Pahta
a central role in medical discourse but also in medical theory and practice, i.e. terms,
such as sign, token and symptom, used in reference to observable entities that signal
the presence of an underlying medical condition or circumstance. His comparison of
the use of variants in the lexical field in different text categories of the corpus indicates
differences in the terminological practices of different medical disciplines. The study
also shows that the Philosophical Transactions, the new medium of cutting-edge sci-
ence, has a distinct style when using this core medical terminology.
In the final chapter, “Intensifiers in competition: The picture from early English
medical writing’, Belén Méndez-Naya and Paivi Pahta examine intensification practices
in two medical genres, treatises and recipes. Focusing on the most frequent intensifiers
identified in earlier research, their study, covering the period 1375-1700, also illus-
trates how EMEMT can be combined with MEMT to obtain a longer diachronic view
of developments in register-specific usage. The authors also compare their findings with
those based on the Helsinki Corpus of English Texts, a multi-genre general-purpose his-
torical corpus. A close analysis of the similar-looking overall patterns of development
indicates that a detailed examination of larger register- and genre-specific datasets like
EMEMT can make a significant contribution to our understanding of the mechanisms
of variation and change. Like Tyrkko’s chapter, this study shows that medical writing is
not a monolithic register, but different varieties, anchored in different sociocultural and
disciplinary contexts and traditions of writing, show different patterns in their discur-
Sive practices.
