2. Changing scientific thought-styles: Authorities and knowledge
As a continuation of the medieval era, medical writing in the sixteenth century was
largely based on the writings of the ancient authorities. This scholastic approach relied
on the knowledge of the past scholars with Hippocrates and Galen in the forefront,
```
and the medical theory derived from the Galenic humoral theory (see e.g. Siraisi
```
```
1990). In the course of the seventeenth century, a change from scholasticism to empiri-
```
cism was experienced in medical thinking. Medical writers became more hesitant to
depend solely on the old authorities and began to support more careful examination
of the natural word. Paracelsian and Helmontian chemical medicine became more
widespread, and in general emphasis was given to observation and empirical research
```
(see e.g. Wear 2000). ‘Ihe studies presented in this section chart this development in
```
scientific thinking by analysing references to knowledge, to the sources of knowledge
and to the different knowers, and by surveying the dissemination of the ancient medi-
cal theory over time. In general, the new science with its emphasis on observation
directed medical writers to a more author-centred approach, which allowed modi-
```
fication and criticism of the earlier knowledge base; at the same time, the sources of
```
knowledge in the top layers of medical science became more varied and widened to
include contemporary physicians. In addition to the studies discussed in this section,
the changing thought-styles are also seen as an underlying factor in most of the other
articles reviewed in the chapter.
```
In relation to scholasticism and empiricism, Taavitsainen (2002) has analysed
```
speech act verbs of reporting and verbs of observation in MEMT and EMEMT from
the point of view of historical discourse analysis. Taavitsainen notes that although most
medical texts continue the old tradition of scholastic evidentiality in the seventeenth
century, there is a rise in medical writing that concentrates on empirical reports. Lexical
searches reveal that the verb say was the most typical reporting verb used in scholastic
contexts but also verbs expressing certainty and power such as command were used to
quote authorities. Unlike scholastic texts, texts from the period of empiricism favour
verbs of observation and cognition, such as think and understand with the first-person
singular. In such texts, the author describes the experiment, and the process of knowl-
edge construction includes more personal reasoning. Early traces of this method can
already be found in late medieval texts, but it becomes more common in Philosophical
```
Transactions. Additionally, metatext is used to communicate with the reader; apart from
```
recipes, metatext is common in the other medical genres examined in the study, i.e. in
learned general treatises and textbooks, surgical texts and regimens. Metatextual com-
ments with reporting verbs also show a trend towards more author-oriented writing.
The change in scientific thought-styles reflected in overt references to sources
```
of knowledge has also been studied by Taavitsainen (2009a). Two sets of overt refer-
```
ences to sources of knowledge in EMEMT were examined: first, references to specific
Explorations through Early Modern English Medical Texts 153
classical authorities such as Galen and Hippocrates and, second, references to gen-
eral categories of people, such as philosophers and physicians. Frequent reference to
classical authorities is a typical feature of learned medieval medical texts, and it reflects
```
the scholastic scientific paradigm (Taavitsainen & Pahta 1998). In contrast, the fre-
```
quency of classical authors as a source of knowledge decreases during the early mod-
ern period. The change is gradual and the old scholastic discourse patterns continue
well into the seventeenth century. As references to ancient authorities decrease, refer-
ences to general categories of people as sources of knowledge increase, especially in
learned medical writing. These references are also increasingly used to denote specific
contemporary people, whose identities do not need to be explicated. This development
is related to the rise of empiricism, which sees scientific knowledge as something that
is created by the discourse community of scientists. While the above general trends are
clearly observable in EMEMT, the different corpus categories differ in the ascription
of sources of knowledge. For instance, in more popular texts, references to classical
authorities gain a function of making the text seem more learned.
The modification of medical thinking has been analysed by Hiltunen and Tyrkké
```
(2009) through lexical items (17 nouns and 3 verbs) that refer to knowledge from
```
the Late Middle English period to Present-day English. The data assessed are learned
medical texts from four different periods covered by samples from MEMT, EMEMT,
ARCHER and Medicor, which represent different phases in science from scholasti-
cism to constructivism.' Generally, the frequencies of nouns referring to knowledge
```
decrease during the time span, although nouns referring to itemized knowledge (e.g.
```
```
data, information) become notably more common in the later periods. This change
```
signals a growing intent to concentrate on results and their significance in the aca-
```
demic field. Further, in the Late Middle English period, general knowledge nouns (e.g.
```
```
understanding, wisdom) are often used didactically to comment on what is useful for
```
the reader to know, while in the early modern data, the attention is on writer-oriented
```
knowledge. As with nouns, verbs of knowing (know, understand and wit) become
```
less frequent during the four periods, marking again a shift from Gnostic quotational
references to more evaluative knowledge. Instead of theory-based considerations of
knowledge, medical scholars became able to gain exact data from clinical studies that
lessened the need to discuss the act of knowing as such and resulted in a discourse that
is oriented towards the medical community.
