4. Multilingualism and code-switching
```
Pahta (2007 and forthcoming a) has examined multilingual practices in Early Modern
```
English medical texts, focusing on code-switching. The studies show that code-switching
is frequent in early modern medical writing, reflecting the multilingual nature of the
medical register in the period, with the vernacular slowly overtaking Latin. The code-
switches are located in EMEMT material by identifying potential foreign words in an
automatically generated word list and then by close reading of the passages in which
these words appear. The most frequently occurring languages in addition to English are
Latin and Greek, but other languages are also occasionally used. Most code-switches
occur in domain-specific contexts and are connected with the discourse of domain-
specific knowledge. Three partially overlapping contexts are identified as frequent
sites of foreign-language segments in EMEMT data: medical terminology, expressions
of intertextuality, and recipes. Pahta has compared code-switching in Early Modern
English data with what has previously been found out about medieval practices, dis-
covering much continuity, but also changes. The three major code-switching contexts
are carried over from the medieval period, whereas some code-switch types used in
medieval medical texts become rarer or even obsolete. While code-switching was com-
mon in various types of religious passages in medieval medical writing, this no longer
appears in Early Modern English data, mainly because religious passages are no longer
so prominently present in early modern medical texts. Also, the use of code-switching
as a text-structuring device becomes less frequent. Latin headings and sub-headings
become rarer, but Latin closing formulae at the end of texts are still used. A new practice
of using Latin or Greek in mottos at the beginning of texts appears.
