shows that medical dialogues were rare in the medieval period, increasing in number
from the mid-sixteenth century onwards. Many of the Early Modern English dialogues
identified and described in the study have been included in the EMEMT corpus.
Taavitsainen identifies two distinct traditions, both used mainly for didactic purposes,
namely the scholastic question-answer formula and the mimetic dialogue. The ques-
tion-answer formula is the less conversational of the two, containing questions that are
followed by monologic answer passages. The mimetic dialogues are closer to natural
dialogues, containing more interactional features, such as speech acts of everyday con-
versations. The mimetic dialogues may sometimes contain entertaining or humorous
passages to broaden the appeal of the text. Texts often contain traces of both dialogue
traditions, and sometimes a text may begin as a dialogue, but revert to a wholly mono-
logic format later on.
