10. The development of a new genre: Philosophical Transactions
The issuing of the medical journal Philosophical Transactions in 1665 signified a new
```
phase in medical writing. Gotti (forthcoming) observes the development of special-
```
ized discourse in the Philosophical Transactions from the first volume onwards. The
journal represented a new mode of communication in the vernacular that promoted
correspondence through new genres. Gotti reviews four genres within the Philosophi-
cal Transactions: news items, experimental accounts, letters and book reviews. The
news items can be portrayed as descriptions of curious new things, and they aimed at
attracting attention and research interest. Moreover, experimental accounts that were
rare in the early issues soon became popular: the accounts were short narrations of
experiments in the active voice, but also the passive was used when the writers reported
routine activities they had carried out with different apparatuses during the experi-
ment. The narration was usually very detailed and intended to prove the accuracy of
the experiment. Most contributions in the first issues of the journal were still given in
the form ofa letter, and these often provoked long chains of communication. Finally,
the book reviews typically gave a summary of the book in question and contained little
actual evaluation. The Philosophical Transactions increased the community of writers
```
and introduced new modes of discourse; the issues paved the way to the publication
```
of new journals and periodicals on specific topics. The journal also made the experi-
mental essay important, although the genre of experimental essay later evolved from
author-oriented writing into essays that concentrated on the object of study.
