11. Conclusion
The studies reviewed in this chapter have used EMEMT to study diverse topics, rang-
ing from lexical, syntactic, and discursive to semantic and pragmatic. Although the
attention is on linguistic features, the studies also relate their findings to the prevailing
scientific thought-styles. The shift from scholastic to empirical thinking is observed,
for instance, in the distribution of verbs of reporting and knowing and references to
sources of knowledge. As medical writing increasingly discusses results of scientific
experiments and their reliability, there is a growth in the use of evaluative knowledge
words and in epistemic stance markers expressing certainty.
Furthermore, the syntactic studies show that during the early modern period
abstract meanings in prepositional phrases modifying nouns become more com-
```
mon; this development can again be related to empiricism but is also affected by the
```
increasing tendency to favour nominalizations. Additionally, medical texts of the early
modern period exhibit multilingual practices that account for the high quantity of
code-switching. The discourse forms of medical writing are on the move during the
early modern period. New or proliferating genres of the period include medical dia-
logues, news reports, scientific journals and pamphlets. Narratives are occasionally
166 Anu Lehto, Raisa Oinonen & Paivi Pahta
used in medical texts for literary purposes. As an example of the findings on lexis
and definitions, the medical texts use various methods to define concepts including
synonyms and translations.
Many of the studies record a difference in the analysed linguistic features according
to corpus categories or the aimed audience of the texts. In remedybooks, for instance,
the works written for lay audiences contain more references to the readers, while quo-
tations are added to texts targeted at professional readership. Similar contrast can be
seen in works discussing humoral theory: the concept of humour is explained more
carefully in professional texts than in popular books.
As the survey of previous studies in EMEMT shows, research interest in the
corpus has covered a wide variety of elements in medical texts on different levels of
language. Nevertheless, the vast scope of the EMEMT corpus undoubtedly offers many
possibilities for future research on early modern medical writing.
