4. Sign terms in specific categories of writing
The EMEMT corpus is organized into six categories on the basis of extralinguistic,
sociohistorical principles. This categorization allows us to observe that during the
early modern period, the medical profession was only beginning to become organised
and that consequently several traditions of writing, each with distinctive lexical and
discursive practices, can be identified.
In the following, three developmental paths are identified for the use of sign
```
terms. The first of these, learned writing (see 4.1), represents medical texts written and
```
```
circulated principally within the profession. The second, recipe collections (see 4.2),
```
```
represents apothecary texts, a distinct category of writing. Finally, health guides (see
```
```
4.3), represents medical texts written for the increasingly literate middling classes. The
```
borders between the categories have deliberately been left fuzzy to accommodate the
```
nascent nature of medical writing at this time; cut and dried categorizations are dif-
```
ficult to draw, and to do so would be ill-advised.
The examination focuses on the proportional distribution of usage between the
different terms.'® The distribution of sign terms within the categories demonstrates
how learned authors paid significantly more attention to systemic indicators of ail-
ments than their less learned rivals. This stands to reason: while physical signs are
easy for anyone to observe,the relationship between more complex conditions and
supposed underlying causes requires more knowledge and is often based on a long
tradition of expertise.
