4.2 Recipe collections
Apothecaries made up the third group of organized medical professionals in early
modern England. Although ostensibly limited to manufacturing medicines and topical
cures, many apothecaries in fact functioned as de facto physicians, sometimes under the
```
moniker of “apothecary-physicians” (see Wear 2000: 464-466). This became a major
```
issue of contention between apothecaries and the other medical professions particularly
during the seventeenth century. By and large the apothecaries had little formal educa-
tion, if we understand formal to refer to mastery of the principles of natural philosophy
believed to underlie human physiology. Sixteenth-century apothecary terminology was
at best a mélange of Latin and Greek, with a smattering of other more exotic languages
```
(Hebrew and Arabic in particular) thrown in. Apothecaries habitually used corrupt
```
