5. Conclusions
The findings reported here highlight two things. Firstly, it appears likely that changes
in the proportional differences between signifier terms accurately reflect the concomi-
tant broader developments in the field of medical writing, as attested by medical his-
tory. Although we must be careful not to draw too far-reaching conclusions on the
basis of a single, relatively small lexical field, the results make the case that changes in
professional word stock can be used in the study of more significant underlying devel-
opments in styles of thought.
Corpus evidence has shown that when it comes to the use of sign terms, surgical
writing differed to a significant extent from the other learned traditions. However, it is
clear that this difference cannot be explained by the surgeons’ lower level of education.
Rather than being more prone to rely on vernacular idiom, surgical writers appar-
ently took their cues from the continental tradition which was significantly ahead of
England and Scotland in the craft of surgery. Likewise, the findings have suggested that
the use of the vernacular term token declined dramatically at the end of the sixteenth
century, and that symptom by contrast went from a rare foreign term into broad use
in learned medical writing over a relatively short period in the seventeenth century.
Overall, the findings show a gradual lexical shift away from the vernacular, and toward
more specialized terminology.
Secondly, the benefits of domain-specific lexical studies are also brought to the
fore. The evidence presented here reinforces the understanding that medical writing
was not a monolithic construction even in - perhaps especially in - the early modern
period, but rather a mixed bag of different traditions of thinking and writing. Had this
study been conducted without sensitivity to the differences between these traditions
and styles of writing, the use of medical sign terms would have come across in a vastly
different and perhaps even a misleading way. Therefore, instead of treating medicine,
or any other field of specialized language use for that matter, in simplistic terms, this
study supports the view that whenever possible, attention should be paid to the inter-
nal complexities of seemingly well-defined fields of writing.
