3. Browsing the corpus
True to its name, EMEMT Presenter makes it very easy simply to browse through the
corpus and read the individual text extracts. For example, a good way of getting to
know the corpus would be to read the category descriptions in Part II and browse
through the texts at the same time.
As discussed above, the basic organization of the corpus is reflected as a hierarchi-
```
cal tree structure displayed on the left side of the screen (see Image 2). The texts have
```
been organized into five categories on the basis of their extralinguistic features.
Category 2, SPECIFIC TREATISES, is further divided into five more specific subcatego-
ries. A seventh group of texts, called the APPENDIX, is also included. The texts in the
APPENDIX do not constitute a coherent category but rather provide an overview of
contemporary texts at the edges of medicine.
True to the tree metaphor, the categories are called “branches” in EMEMT Pre-
senter. These branches can be treated as ready-made subcorpora, each corresponding
```
to a particular type of text (see Part II of the book for discussion of the principles fol-
```
```
lowed). EMEMT Presenter makes it easy to search and analyse individual branches as
```
well as the whole corpus or individual texts.
```
To read a text in the corpus, simply click on any of the nodes (names of texts). The
```
text is displayed on the right side of the screen. Comments and codes written in square
brackets are markup added by the compilers and they are used to denote noteworthy
details about the texts such as the turning of a page or characters missing from the
```
original text (see Sections 4.3 and 8). If the default settings are in place, marked-up
```
passages will not show up in searches of the corpus nor affect word counts.
