4. Finding words and phrases
The single most important function of a corpus tool is to help us find words and phrases
quickly and efficiently froma large collection of texts. Sometimes you are merely inter-
ested to see whether or not a particular word or phrase is to be found in the corpus at
all, but quite often you also want to know how frequently the word is used, how uni-
formly it is used in different texts, and what kinds of contexts it occurs in.
It is important to keep in mind that a corpus like EMEMT is intended to serve
as a representation of printed medical texts from the early modern period, or from
the period between 1500 and 1700. While a search will accurately return all occur-
rences of the search string within EMEMT, it is possible that the word or phrase
may have been used in contemporary writing. With most searches, it is also advis-
able to pay attention to whether the search string is found uniformly across all
categories and texts, or whether its use appears to be concentrated on a particular
group of texts.
Unlike in a word processor, the search function of a corpus tool like EMEMT Pre-
senter displays words along with their immediate context. These keywords in context,
also known as concordance lines, help us understand how a word is used in authen-
tic language. EMEMT Presenter provides two search functions: “Basic search” and
“Advanced search”. The former is explained in this chapter, the latter in the documen-
tation included within EMEMT Presenter. “Basic search” is more than sufficient for
regular analytical searches of the corpus, while “Advanced search” expands the func-
tionalities to include searches for two items which allows either syntactic or morpho-
logical analysis, and requires more experience with corpus linguistic methodologies.
Basic search is launched by clicking on the magnifying glass icon in the toolbar
or by selecting the “Basic search” option from the “Search” dropdown menu. Either
```
action opens the basic search window (see Image 13).
```
To perform a basic search for a word or phrase, type it in the text box. A cor-
```
pus query is a search for a string of characters; EMEMT Presenter does not make
```
a difference between a search for a single word or a string of words. Likewise, the
program does not automatically recognize inflected forms and spelling variants of
words as instances of the same word. Various ways of dealing with these will be
explained shortly.
