The “Search statistics” window displays basic information about the search in the
upper part of the window, and a grid view of the results in the lower part. Each line
represents an individual text, and displays several kinds of numerical data in columns.
“Returns” gives the total number of occurrences EMEMT Presenter finds in each text -
this is also known as a raw frequency. “Word total” gives the overall word count of
that text. “Percent” gives the proportional prominence of the search word, and finally
“N/X” gives the lexical item’s relative or standardized frequency, that is, raw frequency
divided by a standard divider set from the “Divider value” button at the bottom of
the window.
Relative frequency is an important statistical measure when texts or corpora of
different sizes need to be compared — which is usually the case. Unlike raw frequencies,
relative frequencies can be meaningfully compared between datasets of different size.°
