4.1 Fuzzy searches with wildcards
Sometimes you may be interested in finding alternative word forms which share a
```
common part; typical cases included affixes such as the suffix -ment in words like detri-
```
ment and concealment, for example. Likewise, because the English spelling system was
much more fluid during the early modern period than it is today, the same lexical item
can be found in the corpus spelled in various different ways. Although the standard-
ized version of EMEMT makes it possible to search for many of these words as if they
had been spelled in a standard way, there may be situations where you may want to
search for closely similar forms in the main corpus.®
In corpus linguistics, wildcards are special characters used for indicating to the
computer that the user wants to allow one or more undetermined letters at a particular
position of a search string. The wildcards *and ?, common in other software, can be
used here to increase the flexibility of searches. The question mark stands for a single
unspecified character while the asterisk stands for several of these. You can use more
than one question mark to stand for more than one character, but only one asterisk
is allowed as this stands for more than one character anyway. For example, if a user is
interested in finding all words formed using the aforementioned nominal suffix - ment,
he or she can use the search string *ment. This tells EMEMT Presenter to look for any
and all words ending in -ment. There are no restrictions concerning the use of ques-
tion marks. A search for “t?ken” would find token and taken, while “t?k?n” would also
retrieve forms like tokyn and takyn.
8. See the chapter by Lehto, Baron, et al. for discussion of the principles followed in the
spelling standardization. Wildcard searches can be particularly valuable when searching for
proper nouns and medical terms with no modern equivalent.
