6. Analysis for style and content: Clusters and keyness
EMEMT Presenter also makes available two more advanced search functions. These
rely on computational power to identify patterns in language use which you might
find difficult to identify otherwise. Unlike regular corpus searches, cluster and key-
ness analysis do not require an initial search word. Instead, the computer will identify
potentially interesting features.
Note that both cluster and keyness analyses are best performed on the standard-
ized version of the corpus. Because both are based on counting occurrences of word
forms, spelling variation plays a considerable role in the results. Unless the forms have
been standardized beforehand, EMEMT Presenter does not know how to count all dif-
ferent spelling variants of a given word by default and will instead count each unique
form separately.
6.1 Cluster analysis
In corpus linguistics, a cluster is a string of two or more words that occurs repeatedly
```
in a text or a corpus. Clusters can be either fixed phrases (“good morning”, “God
```
```
bless you”) or other types of expressions that for one reason or another are repeated
```
```
(“In this chapter’, “it is effective for”). In historical linguistics, the identification of
```
stylistic or formulaic patterns of language use is one of the most important uses of
cluster analysis.
Finding clusters is easy with EMEMT Presenter. Unlike regular searches, which
require a query word to start with, cluster analysis makes use of computational power
and looks for any repeatedly occurring word strings of a required length. As can
be expected, short clusters of two or three words are very common and usually not
