6.2 Keyness
In recent years, much attention has been devoted to keyness in corpus linguistics. The
objective of keyness analysis is to use computational power to automatically identify
unusually frequent words in a text or a small corpus, as compared to a larger corpus.
The former is known as a target text, the latter as a reference corpus.
EMEMT Presenter performs keyness analysis by comparing two word lists with
one another and identifying the frequency differences of individual words. The two
word lists can be compiled from individual texts, collections of texts, or from the entire
262 Jukka Tyrkké, Raymond Hickey & Ville Marttila
corpus. Remember that you can also use the prepared word lists of the individual cat-
```
egories and of the entire corpus (see 5.3).!%
```
Standardized frequencies are used for the comparison because the two word lists
are likely to have been compiled from differently sized groups of texts. For example,
when searching for key words in an individual text and comparing it to the rest of
the category the text belongs to, you could find that the individual text extract was,
say, 10,000 words long while the category contained, say, 200,000 words. If EMEMT
Presenter was to compare the raw frequencies of words, the larger corpus would likely
yield higher numbers of almost all words. This would not be very helpful.'* By using
relative frequencies you mitigate the effect of the difference in word count.
To perform a keyness analysis, make sure you have the word lists of your target
text and reference corpus already compiled. Note that the word lists should have been
compiled and saved with only the option “Relative frequency N/#” ticked. If the word
lists were saved with more than one set of numerical data, EMEMT Presenter would
not know which column of information you want to compare.
When you have the word lists ready, click on the “Keyness” icon or select
```
“Keyness in texts” under the “Search” dropdown menu. A new window will open (see
```
```
Image 49).
```
Next, load the two word lists into the two list boxes. The one on the left is for the
target corpus, the one on the right for the reference corpus. Click on the two open
folder icons in the toolbar and select the relevant word list from your computer.
