8. Mark up conventions in EMEMT
The texts of EMEMT are presented as plain ASCII text files for compatibility with
a wide range of corpus tools on different computers and with different operating
systems. Since early modern printed books contain many features which cannot be
captured using ASCII character encoding, special markup is used to represent those
features which have been considered essential for the understanding of the corpus
texts. These features and the markup conventions used to represent them in the corpus
are outlined in detail below.
270 Jukka Tyrkké, Raymond Hickey & Ville Marttila
8.1 File names and text headers
The file names of the corpus texts are made up of the publication year of the text, the
```
name of the author (if known), and the short title of the text separated by underscore
```
```
characters (_). Works consisting of multiple texts, of which several are included in
```
the corpus, have a descriptive label of the particular text appended to the end of the
file name.
```
Examples: 1561_Braunschweig_HomishApothecarye.txt
```
1525_SeyngeOfUryns.txt
1539_Moulton_MyrrourOrGlasseOfHelth_Astrology.txt
In addition to the file name, the text contained in each file is identified by a header,
```
enclosed within tags (see below), consisting of the name of the author and the short
```
title of the text.
```
Example: [ATrevisa, John: On the properties of things]
```
8.2 Layout and textual structure
The structure of the corpus texts follows the structure of the original printed text down
to the level of word unit. The word-division follows that of the original as closely as
possible, ambiguous cases being decided in favor of normalization. However, cases
where two separate words are clearly printed together with no intervening space have
been run together in the transcription, and parts of compound words printed clearly
apart have been reproduced with the intervening space.
8.2.1 Line division
The line division of the text follows that of the original, with each line ending with a
```
space and a Windows-style hard line break (CR+LF). In cases where a word crosses
```
a line break, the line break has been moved to the end of the word according to the
following principles:
Simple words divided by a line break have been transcribed at the end of the line
containing the initial part of the word, regardless of the presence or absence of a hyphen.
```
Example: phy or phy- -— _ physicke
```
sicke sicke
Compound words that are split by a line break and whose initial part ends with a
hyphen before the line break are transcribed on the line containing the initial part of
the word, with the hyphen included in the appropriate place.
```
Example: ther- — _ ther-of
```
of
