Compound words that are split by a line break, whose initial part does not end in a
hyphen before the line break, and whose spelling in the text cannot be considered fixed
have their two parts transcribed separately on their own lines.
```
Example: ther — ther
```
of of
8.2.2 Paragraphs
Paragraphs of text in the original text are indicated in the corpus by following them
```
with an extra line consisting of a single empty space and a hard line break (CR+LF),
```
```
regardless of the visual method of paragraph division employed in the original (extra
```
```
leading, indentation, etc.). Also the last paragraph of the text is followed by an empty
```
line. In cases where the paragraph break coincides with a page break, the empty line
separating the paragraphs is placed before the page number code of the new page
```
(see Pagination below), as the paragraph is considered to end before the page does.
```
8.2.3. Headings
Headings, including both main and subheadings on various levels, are indicated by
enclosing them within tags consisting of opening and closing square brackets and
closing curly brackets.
```
Example: _ [}...}]
```
Headings follow the same lineation conventions as paragraphs, i.e. headings are fol-
```
