1. Introduction
```
The corpus of Early Modern English Medical Texts (EMEMT) provides an innovative
```
new addition to historical corpora by issuing two versions of the transcribed texts:
in addition to the faithful reproductions of the source texts, EMEMT is equipped
with normalized versions of the medical texts containing standardized spellings. The
advantage of normalization is that it improves the precision of word lists, allowing
more simple searches with one word form as well as enabling key word and colloca-
```
tion analysis on historical material (see Baron et al. 2009). Spelling variation is after
```
all a prominent feature in the EMEMT corpus and in the Early Modern English
period in general, although variation in spelling declines towards the end of the
seventeenth century.
The standardized texts are included as a separate tree in the corpus software
EMEMT Presenter, and the texts can be used for corpus searches and other corpus
linguistic methods in the same way as the non-standardized texts. The normaliza-
tion was processed automatically with a manually trained version of the VARD
```
(Variant Detector) software that is specifically developed to handle spelling varia-
```
tion in texts from the Early Modern English era.! Almost 73 per cent of detected
variant tokens in EMEMT were standardized to modern spellings, and the total
number of non-normalized detected variant tokens remaining in the standardized
1. The normalization was made as a joint project of the Scientific Thought-styles team
