3. Nonstandard spelling and EMEMT
Variation of orthography was a common trait in the Early Modern English period
due to a lack of unifying norms of writing. The legacy of Middle English spell-
ing continued, originating from different regional orthographies and scribes,
```
who were often untrained in the writing of English (Scragg 1974: 26; Nevalainen
```
Improving the precision of corpus methods 281
```
2006: 29-30). However, a gradual change towards a more consistent spelling was
```
already taking place. The development towards standardization was initiated
by the Chancery Standard in the fourteenth and fifteenth centuries, and in the
Early Modern English period orthography was further shaped by the standard-
izing effect of the printing press. At the same time, variation in spelling continued
in part because printers intentionally varied the spellings to justify the lines of
```
type (Potter 1969: 40). Spelling, nonetheless, became fairly systematic by the
```
middle of the seventeenth century, although printers rarely employed entirely
consistent spellings even during the latter half of the seventeenth century
```
(Scragg 1974: 71, 80).
```
Some regular spelling conventions in the early modern era included interchange-
```
able use of (u) and (v), until (v) came to mark the consonant form in the 1630s; at the
```
```
same instance, (j) took the consonant function from (i) (Gérlach 1991: 48; cf. Scragg
```
```
1974: 81). Further, final (e) was often added to words as in soule, and consonants
```
```
were doubled as in painefull (e.g. Gérlach 1991: 47).* Additionally, final (ie) became
```
```
standardized to (y) as in bodie/body, and medial (y) became <i) in words such as hym/
```
```
him, or alternatively (ai) in the middle of words as in brayne/brain and (ay) at the end
```
```
of words (Barber 1997: 4; Scragg 1974: 71).
```
The development towards more systematic spelling can be detected in EMEMT
both by observing the corpus texts and by scrutinizing statistical data. Statistical fig-
ures can be calculated on the basis of numerical information produced by VARD dur-
ing automatic normalization. The statistics list the total number of word tokens and
types, the number of recognized modern word forms as well as normalized and non-
normalized variant forms. In total, the frequency of all nonstandard variant tokens in
EMEMT before standardization is 18.2 per cent. It is worth noting, however, that the
statistics occasionally include instances of Latin and medical vocabulary that are not
always recognized by VARD as modern words and are hence included as variants.?
In contrast, a small number of variants will be recognized as modern forms when the
variation equates to a dictionary word, as in then/than.* The frequencies, neverthe-
less, show the diachronic development of spelling variation. As can be expected, there
2. Final <e) is a feature of Kentish orthography. It could also reflect the old inflectional
```
endings, such as in wolde, toke, olde, boke (Scragg 1974: 24; Nevalainen 2006: 32).
```
