4. Automatic standardization of EMEMT
41 VARD
VARD‘, now in version 2.3, is a piece of software designed to deal with spelling
variation in Early Modern English. The software acts as a pre-processor for other
5. Some writers in EMEMT also intentionally employ variant spellings for literary pur-
```
poses: in William Bullein’s Dialogve against feuer pestilence (1564) various spellings are
```
used consciously as markers of the interlocutors’ differing social status and regional dialects
```
(Taavitsainen & Nevanlinna 1999; see also Barber 1997: 11 ff.). The text is included in the
```
APPENDIX in EMEMT.
6. Freely available for academic use, see http://www.comp.lancs.ac.uk/~barona/vard2/.
284 Anu Lehto, Alistair Baron, Maura Ratia & Paul Rayson
corpus linguistic tools by finding standard modern equivalents to spelling vari-
ants, making analysis easier and more accurate. Specialized techniques have been
adapted from modern spell checking tools which are used together to create a list of
potential standard form replacements for each variant. A scoring mechanism based
on previous training is then used to rank these candidates which are offered to the
user who can select the correct form from the list. Alternatively, VARD can select
the top ranked candidate automatically providing its score is above a threshold set
by the user.
Three operating modes are available when using VARD 2.3. An interactive mode
allows the user to manually standardize individual files where the user is presented
with the text, which has detected variant forms highlighted. The user can process vari-
ants by choosing words in the text, using an alphabetical list of variant word types,
or cycling through instances in turn. Standardizations made will be used by VARD
to learn how best to deal with the text or corpus. A training mode allows the user to
```
instruct VARD to train itself from a selection of previously standardized texts; VARD
```
will update its scores and methods as if these texts were processed manually in the
interactive mode. Finally, a batch mode allows the user to automatically standardize a
selection of texts or complete corpus, setting a threshold score for candidate replace-
ments. Previous training from the interactive or training mode will be employed when
deciding on standardizations.
Four methods are employed by VARD when searching for normalized forms:
a phonetic matching algorithm, a list of letter replacement rules, a normalized edit
distance algorithm anda list of previously encountered variants and their standard
equivalents. Each method, depending on the corpus, will have different success rates in
```
finding the correct form (recall) and each will offer different amounts of incorrect sug-
```
```
gestions (precision). For each standardization made during training, VARD recalcu-
```
lates precision and recall for each method, whilst also adjusting its variant to standard
form list and dictionary, used for detecting variants and finding replacements. When
presented with a variant, a list of candidate replacements is produced, each candidate
has a recall and precision predicted based on the previous evidence, and these are
combined into an F-Score which equates to VARD’s confidence for that candidate.
By adjusting VARD’s replacement threshold, the user has control over how many
standardizations VARD makes automatically. By setting a higher threshold, fewer
```
replacements are made due to fewer candidates having a high enough score (lower
```
```
recall); however, variants which are standardized are more often replaced with the cor-
```
```
rect form due to VARD being more confident of these replacements (higher precision).
```
```
Conversely, setting a low threshold will yield more standardizations (higher recall) but
```
standardizations are more likely to be incorrect due to VARD being less confident of
```
the top candidate (lower precision). Striking a balance between precision and recall is
```
always a difficult task and will depend on the purpose of the standardization, among
other factors.
Improving the precision of corpus methods 285
```
