```
```
details see Baron and Rayson (2009), where the tool's recent development is discussed
```
and evaluated, although it should be noted that the tool has been improved further for
the release of version 2.3 since this publication.
4.2 Training and testing
Given the size of the EMEMT corpus with over two million words, it was not possible
to normalize each corpus text separately with VARD. Therefore, the texts were nor-
malized automatically after training the software with manually processed samples.
Training improves the results noticeably since the software learns which replacement
methods are most advantageous and adjusts the precision scores during manual
```
normalization (see above and Baron & Rayson 2009).
```
In EMEMT, the training data was 36,000 words in total. The initial training mate-
```
rial (24,000 words) contained 24 text extracts chosen from each category and fifty-
```
```
year time period of the corpus. In addition, 24 samples of 500 words (12,000 words
```
```
total) were generated by randomly selecting small portions of text from the corpus.
```
The interactive mode of VARD was used to manually standardize these texts, in turn
training the software.
In order to establish the best threshold to use when automatically standardizing
the whole corpus, VARD was trained with three quarters of the manually standardized
samples and recall and precision calculated for the automatic standardization of the
remaining test quarter of manually standardized samples at different thresholds. The
testing showed that the best possible results were gained at a 75 per cent threshold.
This threshold kept the precision high at 98.8 per cent and alloweda recall of 75.8 per
```
cent for word tokens (and 72.9 per cent for word types), i.e. 75.8 per cent of tokens
```
classified as variants by VARD in the test portion were correctly standardized. The
possible ratios of precision and recall obtained by choosing a different threshold are
