As can be seen, preference was given to high precision score in order to avoid vari-
ants being replaced incorrectly. A lower threshold would have increased recall but
at the cost of precision. High precision was considered essential since erroneous
replacements would cause even more imprecise results than the variant forms in the
non-standardized texts.
One further step in the normalizing was to check that all high-frequency variant
forms that did not represent two different words were being standardized. The purpose
was to ensure the accuracy of a frequency list retrieved from the standardized EMEMT
texts in relation to high-frequency words. Therefore, all nonstandard word types that
had a raw frequency higher than 65 were scrutinized, and words relating to medical
terminology were examined if their frequency was between 40 and 65. The word types
above the raw frequency of 65 accounted for 3,227 types, and altogether 4,698 types
were above the raw frequency of 40. Since VARD does not process contextual or seman-
tic data of words at the moment, the contexts of the high-frequency words were anal-
ysed. This made it possible to normalize words that potentially have several meanings,
but appear only in one sense in EMEMT, Asa result, longes, for example, was normalized
to lungs since longes was not used as a third person singular verb in the corpus. Further,
instances of bee were standardized to be and to bee accordingly, although VARD does
not normalize bee as a default because of the multiple meanings of the variant.
4.3 Conventions used in standardizing EMEMT
The choices made during training VARD affect the standardization, and therefore a set
of established conventions were followed in normalizing EMEMT. First of ali, personal
pronouns are not normalized: thou, ye, thee and so on have been left in their origi-
nal forms since normalization would have affected their specific connotations. Only
deviations from standard spellings were corrected, e.g. thyne was normalized to thine.
However, archaic word endings of verbs such as the present tense third person singu-
```
lar form -th were normalized to modern forms; therefore, sayth, for instance, is stan-
```
dardized to says. The high-frequency words hath and doth, on the other hand, were
not normalized since they refer both to the singular and plural forms in the corpus.
```
Further, abbreviations were left as they were; this principle concerns instances such as
```
```
y=e=, +R (recipe), the ampersand e& (signifying both and and et), and Arist. (Aristo-
```
```
tle) that are written as abbreviations in the normalized versions as well. Tildes were
```
```
normalized to (n) or (m), although the normalized texts still contain occurrences of
```
non-replaced tildes. As a rule, names were not changed to standardized forms, except
```
for names of authorities; additionally, the Latin and English versions of the names of
```
authorities as well as medical substances and plants were kept apart.
The dictionary of VARD is based on the British National Corpus and the Spell
```
Checker Oriented Word Lists (SCOWL). During manual training, preference was
```
additionally given to the Oxford English Dictionary Online. Thus, in cases that allowed
Improving the precision of corpus methods 287
for more than one possible modern spelling, the form listed as the head word in the
OED was chosen. Near synonyms were also kept separate, if the synonymous words
had their own entries in the OED: an example of this is capytle that was standardized
to capitle and not to chapter. These cases are handled as two words with slightly differ-
ent meanings and not as mere examples of spelling variation. An exception to the rule
is chirurgian with its variant forms that were standardized to surgeon, although both
have their own entries in the OED.
