When Langton's and Turner's texts are placed into the wider context of Early
Modern English medical writing, it can be noticed that specialized vocabulary was
further shaped during the period, as expansion in vocabulary and medical terminol-
ogy continued to take place. A considerable number of borrowings and neologisms
were introduced into English particularly between 1530 and 1660 to communicate
```
new concepts and to enrich the vernacular (Gorlach 1991: 136-138). In medical writ-
```
ing, the vocabulary was already expanding radically between 1375 and 1400, and the
```
foundations of medical terminology were created in 1375-1500 (Norri 2004: 109-111).
```
New terminology was needed to describe the widening perceptions of sicknesses
and the human body. However, a contrasting tendency in lexis can be detected at the
same time: medical terminology experienced a significant loss especially towards the
