```
fifteenth and early sixteenth century (Norri 2004: 131). Hence many of the new adop-
```
tions in individual texts did not succeed in becoming established into language use.
6. Conclusion
During the Early Modern English period, orthography gradually became more sys-
tematized, especially since printers adopted more regular spelling conventions at
the latter half of the seventeenth century. Despite the standardizing influence of the
extralinguistic developments, nonstandard spellings are frequently encountered in
early modern writing: in the non-standardized texts in EMEMT, the portion of unrec-
ognized words is over 18 per cent according to VARD. For corpus studies, the high
degree of spelling variation in historical material poses difficulties in terms of accu-
racy. The standardized spellings, however, help to improve the use of corpus linguistics
approaches including key word and collocation analysis. To facilitate these methods,
the number of nonstandard spelling variants in EMEMT was reduced noticeably by
automatic standardization: the percentage of unknown variants went down to under
5 per cent in the normalized texts. Thus the standardized corpus texts in EMEMT
aim to gain more precise results and in general to advance the use of corpus linguistic
methods on historical texts.
